# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: technocracy-movement
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] In commerce and industry, **24/7** or **24-7 service** (usually pronounced "twenty-four seven") is service that is available at any time of day, 24 hours, and every day of the week, 7 days.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] An alternate orthography is **24×7** (usually pronounced "twenty-four by seven").
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Less commonly used are the terms **24/7/52** (adding "52 weeks") and **24/7/365** (adding "365 days") make it clear that service is available every day of the year including the one extra day on leap years.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Synonyms include **around-the-clock service** (with/without hyphens) and **all day every day**, especially in British English, and **nonstop service**, but the latter can also refer to other things, such as public transport services which go between two stations without stopping.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] The *Oxford English Dictionary* (OED) defines the term as "twenty-four hours a day, seven days a week; constantly".
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] It lists its first reference to 24/7 to be from a 1983 story in the US magazine *Sports Illustrated* in which Louisiana State University basketball player Jerry Reynolds describes his jump shot in just such a way: 24–7–365.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] 24/7 service is employed in many settings including commercial businesses, emergency services, transport, utilities, certain industrial processes, and some human services.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] 24/7 services may also include taxicabs, security services, and in densely populated urban areas, construction crews.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Public 24/7 services often include those provided by emergency medical providers, police, fire and emergency telephone numbers, such as 9-1-1 in North America.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Transport services like airports, airlines, and ferry services, and in some cases trains and buses, may provide 24-hour service.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Examples of public transport services operating 24/7 include the New York City Subway, Staten Island Railway, PATH, PATCO, the Copenhagen Metro, and the Red Line and Blue Line of the Chicago "L".
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Many networks run a reduced night service schedule.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Industrial and manufacturing facilities—especially those that operate near or at capacity, or which depend upon processes (such as production lines) that are costly to suspend—often provide 24/7 services.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Similarly, utilities generally must provide multiple 24/7 services.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] For instance, an electricity provider will handle outage reports 24/7 and dispatch emergency repair technicians 24/7, in addition to monitoring electrical infrastructure and producing electricity at all times.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] The same applies to telecommunications and internet service providers.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Many crisis centers and crisis hotlines provide 24/7 services.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Many 24/7 services operate continuously at all times with complete shift staff.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] 24/7 services that can utilize virtual offices, such as call centers, may employ daytime agents in alternating time zones.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] In some cases, 24/7 services may be temporarily unavailable under certain circumstances.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Such scenarios may include scheduled maintenance, upgrades or renovation, emergency repair, and injunction.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] 24/7 services which depend upon the physical presence of employees at a given location may also be interrupted when a minimum number of employees cannot be present due to scenarios such as extreme weather, death threats, natural disasters, or mandatory evacuation.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Some 24/7 services close during major holidays.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] 24/7 services often employ complex schemes that ensure their resistance to potential disruption, resilience in the event of disruption, and minimum standards of overall reliability.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Critical infrastructure may be supported by failover systems, electric generators, and satellite communications.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] In the event of catastrophic disaster, some 24/7 services prepare entirely redundant, parallel infrastructures, often in other geographic regions.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] At the beginning of the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, many stores ended 24/7 operations, ostensibly on a temporary basis, in order to clean and sanitize their establishments.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] After the widespread availability of vaccines, however, many such businesses have not returned to 24-hour service for a variety of reasons.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Some proprietors in the United States originally blamed pandemic unemployment benefits for a lack of workers, yet employers still struggled to resume pre-pandemic hours after these programs ended, citing continued staff shortages and demands for better working conditions among jobseekers.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Many businesses that were once broadly open for 24/7 operations only resumed such service across some of their establishments or have ended 24/7 operations altogether, as in the case of Walmart.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] 24/7 workplaces can put employees under conditions that limit their personal life choices and development.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Calls for a rehumanisation of the 24/7 workplace have therefore been voiced.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Some have also remarked on the "collective mania" especially in the US that takes a sort of pride in the "work at all times" attitude exemplified by the 24/7 concept.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] In England, Wales, and Northern Ireland, the Sunday trading laws prevent many stores from truly opening 24/7, but they sometimes advertise as such.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] Some core services such as filling stations are exempt from the law requiring them to close.
[src:technocracy-movement/24-7] A campaign against changing the law was supported by many bodies, including the Church of England, the Church in Wales, and many secular bodies in an effort called Keep Sunday Special.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Klein and Thompson argue that the regulatory environment in many liberal cities, while well intentioned, stymies development.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] They write that liberals have been more concerned with blocking bad economic development than promoting good development since the 1970s.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] They say that Democrats have focused on the process rather than results and favored stasis over growth by backing zoning regulations, developing strict environmental laws, and tying expensive requirements to public infrastructure spending.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] They present the abundance agenda as a way to initiate new economic conditions that will diminish the appeal of the "socialist left" and the "populist-authoritarian right".
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] The book received a mixed reception from critics.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Some praised the scope and clarity of the ideas presented, while others viewed the book as ignoring trade-offs and negative impacts.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] At the time of the book's publication, Ezra Klein worked as a columnist for *The New York Times*, while Derek Thompson held a position as staff writer for *The Atlantic*.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] The book originated from an essay published by Thompson in *The Atlantic* in January 2022.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] In an interview, the two authors talked about their differing perspectives when writing *Abundance*.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Thompson stated that he felt "more comfortable starting with economics or technology", while Klein brought a viewpoint "versed in modern politics and political history".
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Henry Grabar of *Slate* praised the book for being "unabashed in synthesizing good ideas".
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] In another positive review, Benjamin Wallace-Wells of *The New Yorker* described Abundance as a "fair-minded book" that "recognizes some of the trade-offs that come with redesigning government for dynamism".
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Writing for *The New York Times*, Samuel Moyn gave a mixed review.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] He questioned the potential consequences of an abundance-driven agenda, wondering whether it could reinforce a culture of consumption as a primary goal.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] He also critiqued the authors' viewpoint as occasionally sounding "like the brief of a few elite finance and tech bros in two or three coastal cities".
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Eric Levitz of *Vox* also provided a mixed review.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] He noted a disconnect between the authors' proposals and the political climate at the time of the book's publication.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] In Levitz's view, pressing issues like the gutting of the federal government and the subversion of court orders made the authors' focus on specific regulatory concerns, like suburban housing codes, seem comparatively minor.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] He further criticized the authors' avoidance of clearly addressing the trade-offs between their policy proposals and traditional progressive ideology.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Similarly, Noah Kazis of *The Guardian* pointed out that the book avoids tackling the more challenging issues directly by failing to specify which procedural barriers should be addressed.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Kazis, however, praised the book for its "clarity, accessibility, and rigour".
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] In a negative review for *The Wall Street Journal*, Barton Swaim criticized the authors for appearing dismissive of American conservatism.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] He also argued that Klein and Thompson's ideas seemed disconnected from the realities of everyday life and ordinary people.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] She said the authors were unclear regarding the specifics of such reforms, as well as centering their arguments primarily on only a few large American cities, while underestimating the negative effects of monopolization in the U.S. economy at large.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] She raised concerns that it could be used in the style of deregulation associated with Ronald Reagan.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Zelizer argued the book centered on two themes: policy and politics.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] On the policy side, Zelizer believed that Klein and Thompson presented a convincing case that removing ineffective governmental practices should be a priority to renew liberalism.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] However, Zelizer was not convinced on the political side, and questioned if there is a political constituency and suggested that institutional reform is only part of the solution.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] The funding coalition and ecosystem promoting Abundance as a movement predates the book by over a decade.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Open Philanthropy has promoted and funded workshops, conferences, and materials related to the themes of the book since 2015.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] The Abundance Conference, sponsored by Arnold Ventures, Open Philanthropy, and Stand Together, began in 2024.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Collectively, these organizations have spent over $120M promoting the themes and ideas of the book via conferences, think tanks, and grants.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Klein delivered the keynote address at the Abundance Summit in 2025, and his co-author Thompson moderated a panel on clean energy infrastructure.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Klein also addressed the Urban Institute's 2025 Housing Policy Conference on themes from the book.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Regional gatherings have also occurred, including a California Abundance Forum in San Francisco, which focused on housing affordability and transit development.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] An "Abundance Elected Network" launched in September 2025, with initial involvement from 120 lawmakers.
[src:technocracy-movement/abundance-klein-and-thompson-book] Some conferences and workshops in the movement are organized by a group called the "Abundance Network", which was founded by Misha Chellam and Zack Rosen.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was born in Braunau am Inn in Austria-Hungary and moved to Germany in 1913.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He was decorated during his service in the German Army in the First World War, receiving the Iron Cross.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1919, he joined the German Workers' Party (DAP), the precursor of the Nazi Party, and in 1921, was appointed the leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, he attempted to seize governmental power in a failed coup in Munich and was sentenced to five years in prison, serving just over a year.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, he dictated the first volume of his autobiography and political manifesto *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] After his early release in 1924, he gained popular support by attacking the Treaty of Versailles as well as promoting pan-Germanism, antisemitism, and anti-communism with charismatic oratory and Nazi propaganda.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He frequently denounced communism as being part of an international Jewish conspiracy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] By November 1932, the Nazi Party held the most seats in the *Reichstag*, but not a majority.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Former chancellor Franz von Papen and other conservative politicians convinced President Paul von Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as chancellor on 30 January 1933.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly thereafter, on 23 March, the *Reichstag* passed the Enabling Act of 1933, which ultimately began the Weimar Republic's transformation into Nazi Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Upon Hindenburg's death on 2 August 1934, Hitler replaced him as head of state and thereafter transformed Germany into a totalitarian dictatorship.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Domestically, Hitler implemented numerous racist policies and sought to deport or kill German Jews.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His first six years in power resulted in rapid economic recovery from the Great Depression, the abrogation of restrictions imposed on Germany after the First World War, and the annexation of territories inhabited by millions of ethnic Germans, which initially gave him significant popular support.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] One of Hitler's key goals was *Lebensraum* (lit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] 'living space') for the German people in Eastern Europe.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His aggressive, expansionist foreign policy is considered the primary cause of World War II in Europe.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 September 1939, Hitler oversaw the German invasion of Poland, thereby causing Britain and France to declare war on Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] After ordering an invasion of the Soviet Union in June 1941, he declared war on the United States in December of the same year.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of 1941, German forces and the European Axis powers occupied most of Europe and North Africa.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] These gains were gradually reversed after 1941 until the Allied forces defeated the German military in 1945.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 29 April 1945, Hitler married his longtime partner, Eva Braun, in the *Führerbunker* in Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] They committed suicide the next day to avoid capture by the Soviet Red Army.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The historian and biographer Ian Kershaw described Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Under Hitler's leadership and racist ideology, the Nazi regime was responsible for the genocide of an estimated six million Jews and millions of other victims, whom he and his followers deemed *Untermenschen* (lit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazis were also responsible for the deliberate killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of civilians killed during World War II was unprecedented in warfare, and the casualties make it the deadliest conflict in history.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's father, Alois Hitler, was the illegitimate child of Maria Schicklgruber.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The baptismal register did not show the name of his father, and Alois initially bore his mother's surname, "Schicklgruber".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1842, Johann Georg Hiedler married Alois's mother.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was brought up in the family of Hiedler's brother, Johann Nepomuk Hiedler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois worked as a civil servant from 1855 until his retirement in 1895.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1876, Alois was made legitimate and his baptismal record annotated by a priest to register Johann Georg Hiedler as Alois's father (recorded as "Georg Hitler").
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois then assumed the surname "Hitler", also spelled "Hiedler", "Hüttler", or "Huettler".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The name is probably based on the German word *Hütte* (lit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] 'hut'), and has the meaning "one who lives in a hut".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi official Hans Frank suggested that Alois's mother had been employed as a housekeeper by a Jewish family in Graz, and that the family's 19-year-old son Leopold Frankenberger had fathered Alois, a claim that came to be known as the Frankenberger thesis.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] No Frankenberger was registered in Graz during that period, and no record has been produced of a Leopold Frankenberger's existence, so historians dismiss the claim that Alois's father was Jewish.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 2025, blood from the sofa in Hitler's study was used by Turi King of the University of Bath for DNA analysis.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The blood was confirmed to be Hitler's by comparing it to that of a male-line relative, and the DNA analysis also showed that Hitler did not have Jewish ancestry through his father.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] "If that was the case, we wouldn't have got the DNA match with him," King said.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Adolf Hitler was born on 20 April 1889 in Braunau am Inn, a town in Austria-Hungary (present-day Austria), close to the border with Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He was the fourth of six children born to Alois Hitler and his third wife, Klara Pölzl.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Three of Hitler's siblings—Gustav, Ida, and Otto—died in infancy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Also living in the household were Alois's children from his second marriage: Alois Jr.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1892, the family moved to Passau, Germany, following Alois's promotion to the customs administration in Passau.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois was promoted and transferred to Linz, Austria, on 1 April 1893, but the rest of the family remained in Passau.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] There, Hitler acquired the distinctive lower Bavarian dialect, rather than Austrian German, which marked his speech throughout his life.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The family returned to Austria and settled in Leonding on 9 May 1894, and in June 1895, Alois retired to Hafeld, near Lambach, where he farmed and kept bees.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler attended *Volksschule* (a state-funded primary school) in nearby Fischlham.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The move to Hafeld coincided with the onset of intense father–son conflicts caused by six-year-old Hitler's refusal to conform to the strict discipline of his school.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois tried to browbeat his son into obedience, while Adolf did his best to be the opposite of whatever his father wanted.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois would also beat his son, although his mother tried to protect him from regular beatings.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois Hitler's farming efforts at Hafeld were unsuccessful, and in 1897, the family moved to Lambach.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The eight-year-old Hitler took singing lessons, sang in the church choir, and even considered becoming a priest.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1898, the family returned permanently to Leonding.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was deeply affected by the death of his younger brother Edmund in 1900 from measles.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler transformed from a confident, outgoing, and conscientious student to a morose, detached boy who frequently clashed with his father and teachers.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Paula Hitler recalled that Adolf was a teenage bully who would often slap her.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Alois had made a successful career in the customs bureau and wanted his son to follow in his footsteps.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later dramatised an episode from this period when his father took him to visit a customs office, depicting it as an event that gave rise to an unforgiving antagonism between father and son, who were both strong-willed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Ignoring his son's desire to attend a classical high school and become an artist, Alois sent Hitler to the *Realschule* in Linz in September 1900.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler rebelled against this decision, and in *Mein Kampf* states that he intentionally performed poorly in school, hoping that once his father saw "what little progress I was making at the technical school he would let me devote myself to my dream".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Like many Austrian Germans, Hitler began to develop German nationalist ideas from a young age.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He expressed loyalty only to Germany, despising the declining Habsburg monarchy and its rule over an ethnically diverse empire.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and his friends used the greeting "Heil", and sang the "Deutschlandlied" instead of the Austrian Imperial anthem.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] After Alois's sudden death on 3 January 1903, Hitler's performance at school deteriorated, and his mother allowed him to leave.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He enrolled at the *Realschule* in Steyr in September 1904, where his behaviour and performance improved.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1905, after passing a repeat of the final exam, Hitler left the school without any ambitions for further education or clear plans for a career.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1907, Hitler left Linz to live and study fine art in Vienna, financed by an orphan's benefits and support from his mother.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He applied for admission to the Academy of Fine Arts Vienna but was rejected twice.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The director suggested Hitler should apply to the School of Architecture, but he lacked the necessary academic credentials because he had not finished secondary school.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 December 1907, his mother died of breast cancer at the age of 47; Hitler was 18 at the time.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1909, Hitler ran out of money and was forced to live a bohemian life in homeless shelters and the Meldemannstraße dormitory.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He earned money as a casual labourer and by painting and selling watercolours of Vienna's sights.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] During his time in Vienna, he pursued a growing passion for architecture and music, attending ten performances of *Lohengrin*, his favourite of Richard Wagner's operas.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In Vienna, Hitler was first exposed to racist rhetoric.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Populists such as mayor Karl Lueger exploited the city's prevalent antisemitic sentiment, occasionally also espousing German nationalist notions for political benefit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] German nationalism was especially widespread in the Mariahilf district, where Hitler then lived.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Georg Ritter von Schönerer became a major influence on Hitler, and he developed an admiration for Martin Luther.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler read newspapers and pamphlets that promoted prejudice and warned of an influx of Eastern European Jews, as well as writings by figures such as Houston Stewart Chamberlain, Charles Darwin, Friedrich Nietzsche, Gustave Le Bon, and Arthur Schopenhauer.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] During his years in Vienna he also developed strong anti-Slavic sentiments.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The origin and development of Hitler's antisemitism remain a matter of debate.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His friend August Kubizek claimed that Hitler was a "confirmed antisemite" before he left Linz.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] However, the historian Brigitte Hamann describes Kubizek's claim as "problematical".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler states in *Mein Kampf* that he first became an antisemite in Vienna, Reinhold Hanisch, who helped him to sell his paintings, disagrees.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sold some of his art through a Jewish businessman named Samuel Morgenstern while living in Vienna.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of Morgenstern's clients were Jewish; for example, a lawyer named Josef Feingold purchased several of Hitler's paintings of Vienna's historical architecture.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Evans states that "historians now generally agree that his notorious, murderous antisemitism emerged well after Germany's defeat in World War I, as a product of the paranoid "stab-in-the-back" explanation for the catastrophe".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler received the final part of his father's estate in May 1913 and moved to Munich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] When he was conscripted into the Austro-Hungarian Army, he journeyed to Salzburg on 5 February 1914 for medical assessment.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] After he was deemed unfit for service, he returned to Munich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler later claimed that he did not wish to serve the Habsburg Empire because of the mixture of races in its army and his belief that the collapse of Austria-Hungary was imminent.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1914, at the outbreak of World War I, Hitler was living in Munich and voluntarily enlisted in the Bavarian Army.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] According to a 1924 report by the Bavarian authorities, allowing Hitler to serve was most likely an administrative error, because as an Austrian citizen, he should have been returned to Austria.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Posted to the Bavarian Reserve Infantry Regiment 16 (1st Company of the List Regiment), he served as a dispatch runner on the Western Front in France and Belgium, spending nearly half his time at the regimental headquarters in Fournes-en-Weppes, well behind the front lines.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1914, he was present at the First Battle of Ypres and in that year was decorated for bravery, receiving the Iron Cross, Second Class.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] During the war, he was saved by his commanding officer, Fritz Wiedemann, who pulled Hitler out of the rubble of a collapsed building while under heavy fire.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] During his service at headquarters, Hitler pursued his artistic interests, drawing cartoons and providing instructions for an army newspaper.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] During the Battle of the Somme in October 1916, he was wounded in the left thigh when a shell exploded in the dispatch runners' dugout.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler spent almost two months recovering in hospital at Beelitz, returning to his regiment on 5 March 1917.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He was present at the Battle of Arras of 1917 and the Battle of Passchendaele.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He received the black Wound Badge on 18 May 1918.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Three months later, in August 1918, on a recommendation by Lieutenant Hugo Gutmann, his Jewish superior, Hitler received the Iron Cross, First Class, a decoration rarely awarded at Hitler's *Gefreiter* rank.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 15 October 1918, he was temporarily blinded in a mustard gas attack and was hospitalised in Pasewalk.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While there, Hitler learned of Germany's defeat, and, by his own account, suffered a second bout of blindness after receiving this news.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler described his role in World War I as "the greatest of all experiences" and was praised by his commanding officers for his bravery.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His wartime experience reinforced his German patriotism, and he was shocked by Germany's capitulation in November 1918.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His displeasure with the collapse of the war effort began to shape his ideology.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Treaty of Versailles stipulated that Germany had to relinquish several of its territories and demilitarise the Rhineland.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The treaty imposed economic sanctions and levied heavy reparations on the country.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Many Germans saw the treaty as an unjust humiliation.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] They especially objected to Article 231, which they interpreted as declaring Germany responsible for the war.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Versailles Treaty and the economic, social, and political conditions in Germany after the war were later exploited by Hitler for political gain.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] After the war, Hitler returned to Munich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Without formal education or career prospects, he remained in the army.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In July 1919, he was appointed *Verbindungsmann* (intelligence agent) of an *Aufklärungskommando* (reconnaissance unit) of the *Reichswehr*, assigned to influence other soldiers and to infiltrate the German Workers' Party (DAP).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At a DAP meeting on 12 September 1919, Party chairman Anton Drexler was impressed by Hitler's oratorical skills.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He gave him a copy of his pamphlet *My Political Awakening*, which contained antisemitic, nationalist, anti-capitalist, and anti-Marxist ideas.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On the orders of his army superiors, Hitler applied to join the party, and within a week was accepted as party member 555 (the party began counting membership at 500 to give the impression they were a much larger party).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made his earliest known written statement about the Jewish question in a 16 September 1919 letter to Adolf Gemlich (now known as the Gemlich letter).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In the letter, Hitler argues that the aim of the government "must unshakably be the removal of the Jews altogether".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At the DAP, Hitler met Dietrich Eckart, one of the party's founders and a member of the occult Thule Society.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Eckart became Hitler's mentor, exchanging ideas with him and introducing him to a wide range of Munich society.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] To increase its appeal, the DAP changed its name to the *Nationalsozialistische Deutsche Arbeiterpartei* (National Socialist German Workers' Party (NSDAP), now known as the "Nazi Party").
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler designed the party's banner of a swastika in a white circle on a red background.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler was discharged from the army on 31 March 1920, and began working full-time for the party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The party headquarters was in Munich, a centre for anti-government German nationalists determined to eliminate Marxism and undermine the Weimar Republic.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In February 1921, already highly effective at crowd manipulation, Hitler spoke to a crowd of over 6,000.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] To publicise the meeting, two truckloads of party supporters drove around Munich waving swastika flags and distributing leaflets.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler soon gained notoriety for his rowdy polemic speeches against the Treaty of Versailles, rival politicians, and especially against Marxists and Jews.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In June 1921, while Hitler and Eckart were on a fundraising trip to Berlin, a mutiny broke out within the Nazi Party in Munich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Members of its executive committee wanted to merge with the Nuremberg-based German Socialist Party (DSP).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler returned to Munich on 11 July and angrily tendered his resignation.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee members realised that the resignation of their leading public figure and speaker would mean the end of the party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler announced he would rejoin on the condition that he would replace Drexler as party chairman, and that the party headquarters would remain in Munich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The committee agreed, and he rejoined the party on 26 July as member 3,680.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler continued to face some opposition within the Nazi Party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Opponents of Hitler in the leadership had Hermann Esser expelled from the party, and they printed 3,000 copies of a pamphlet attacking Hitler as a traitor to the party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In the following days, Hitler spoke to several large audiences and defended himself and Esser, to thunderous applause.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His strategy proved successful, and at a special party congress on 29 July, he was granted absolute power as party chairman, succeeding Drexler, by a vote of 533 to 1.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's vitriolic beer hall speeches began attracting regular audiences.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] A demagogue, he became adept at using populist themes, including the use of scapegoats, who were blamed for his listeners' economic hardships.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used personal magnetism and an understanding of crowd psychology to his advantage while engaged in public speaking.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Historians have noted the hypnotic effect of his rhetoric on large audiences, and of his eyes in small groups.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Early followers included Rudolf Hess, the former air force ace Hermann Göring, and the army captain Ernst Röhm.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Röhm became head of the Nazis' paramilitary organisation, the *Sturmabteilung* (SA, "Stormtroopers"), which protected meetings and attacked political opponents.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] A critical influence on Hitler's thinking during this period was the *Aufbau Vereinigung*, a conspiratorial group of White Russian exiles and early Nazis.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The group, financed with funds channelled from wealthy industrialists, introduced Hitler to the idea of a Jewish conspiracy, linking international finance with Bolshevism.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The programme of the Nazi Party was laid out in their 25-point programme on 24 February 1920.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] This did not represent a coherent ideology, but was a conglomeration of received ideas which had currency in the *völkisch* pan-Germanic movement, such as ultranationalism, opposition to the Treaty of Versailles, distrust of capitalism, as well as some socialist ideas.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] For Hitler, the most important aspect of it was its strong antisemitic stance.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He also perceived the programme as primarily a basis for propaganda and for attracting people to the party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In 1923, Hitler enlisted the help of World War I General Erich Ludendorff for an attempted coup known as the Beer Hall Putsch.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party used Italian Fascism as a model for their appearance and policies.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler wanted to emulate Benito Mussolini's March on Rome in 1922 by staging his own coup in Bavaria, to be followed by a challenge to the government in Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and Ludendorff sought the support of *Staatskommissar* (State Commissioner) Gustav Ritter von Kahr, Bavaria's *de facto* ruler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] However, Kahr, along with Police Chief Hans Ritter von Seisser and Reichswehr General Otto von Lossow, wanted to install a nationalist dictatorship without Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 8 November 1923, Hitler and the SA stormed a public meeting of 3,000 people organised by Kahr in the Bürgerbräukeller, a beer hall in Munich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Interrupting Kahr's speech, he announced that the national revolution had begun and declared the formation of a new government with Ludendorff.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Retiring to a back room, Hitler, with his pistol drawn, demanded and subsequently received the support of Kahr, Seisser, and Lossow.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's forces initially succeeded in occupying the local Reichswehr and police headquarters, but Kahr and his cohorts quickly withdrew their support.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Neither the Army nor the state police joined forces with Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The next day, Hitler and his followers marched from the beer hall to the Bavarian War Ministry to overthrow the Bavarian government, but police dispersed them.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In the failed coup, 16 Nazi Party members and four police officers were killed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler fled to the home of Ernst Hanfstaengl and by some accounts contemplated suicide.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He was depressed but calm when arrested on 11 November 1923 for high treason.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] His trial before the special People's Court in Munich began in February 1924, and Alfred Rosenberg became the temporary leader of the Nazi Party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 April, Hitler was sentenced to five years' *Festungshaft* ('fortress confinement') at Landsberg Prison.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] There, he received friendly treatment from the guards and was allowed mail from supporters and regular visits by party comrades.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Pardoned by the Bavarian Supreme Court, he was released from jail on 20 December 1924, against the state prosecutor's objections.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Including time on remand, Hitler served just over one year in prison.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While at Landsberg, Hitler dictated most of the first volume of *Mein Kampf* (lit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] 'My Struggle'; originally titled *Four and a Half Years of Struggle against Lies, Stupidity, and Cowardice*) at first to his chauffeur, Emil Maurice, and then to his deputy, Rudolf Hess.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The book, dedicated to Thule Society member Dietrich Eckart, was an autobiography and exposition of his ideology.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The book laid out Hitler's plans for territorial expansion as well as transforming German society into a dictatorship based on race.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Throughout the book, Jews are equated with "germs" and presented as the "international poisoners" of society.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] According to Hitler's ideology, the only solution was their extermination.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While Hitler did not describe exactly how this was to be accomplished, his "inherent genocidal thrust is undeniable", according to Ian Kershaw.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Published in two volumes in 1925 and 1926, *Mein Kampf* sold 228,000 copies between 1925 and 1932.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] One million copies were sold in 1933, Hitler's first year in office.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Shortly before Hitler was eligible for parole, the Bavarian government attempted to have him deported to Austria.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Austrian federal chancellor rejected the request on the specious grounds that his service in the German Army made his Austrian citizenship void.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler formally renounced his Austrian citizenship on 7 April 1925.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At the time of Hitler's release from prison, politics in Germany had become less combative, and the economy had improved, limiting Hitler's opportunities for political agitation.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] As a result of the failed Beer Hall Putsch, the Nazi Party and its affiliated organisations were banned in Bavaria.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with the prime minister of Bavaria, Heinrich Held, on 4 January 1925, Hitler agreed to respect the state's authority and promised that he would seek political power only through the democratic process.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The meeting paved the way for the ban on the Nazi Party to be lifted on 16 February.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] However, after an inflammatory speech he gave on 27 February, Hitler was barred from public speaking by the Bavarian authorities, a ban that remained in place until 1927.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] To advance his political ambitions despite the ban, Hitler appointed Gregor Strasser, Otto Strasser, and Joseph Goebbels to organise and enlarge the Nazi Party in northern Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Gregor Strasser steered a more independent political course, emphasising the socialist elements of the party's programme.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The stock market in the United States crashed on 24 October 1929.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The impact in Germany was dire: millions became unemployed, and several major banks collapsed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler and the Nazi Party prepared to take advantage of the emergency to gain support for their party.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] They promised to repudiate the Versailles Treaty, strengthen the economy, and provide jobs.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Great Depression provided a political opportunity for Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Germans were ambivalent about the parliamentary republic, which faced challenges from right- and left-wing extremists.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The moderate political parties were increasingly unable to stem the tide of extremism, and the German referendum of 1929 helped to elevate Nazi ideology.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The elections of September 1930 resulted in the break-up of a grand coalition and its replacement with a minority cabinet.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Its leader, chancellor Heinrich Brüning of the Centre Party, governed through emergency decrees from President Paul von Hindenburg.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Governance by decree became the new norm, paving the way for authoritarian forms of government.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party rose from obscurity to win 18.3 per cent of the vote and 107 parliamentary seats in the 1930 election, becoming the second-largest party in parliament.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler made a prominent appearance at the trial of two Reichswehr officers, Lieutenants Richard Scheringer and Hanns Ludin, in late 1930.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Both were charged with membership in the Nazi Party, at that time illegal for Reichswehr personnel.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The prosecution argued that the Nazi Party was extremist, prompting defence lawyer Hans Frank to call on Hitler to testify.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 September 1930, Hitler testified that his party would pursue political power solely through democratic elections, which won him many supporters in the officer corps.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Brüning's austerity measures brought little economic improvement and were extremely unpopular.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler exploited this by targeting his political messages specifically at people who had been affected by the inflation of the 1920s and the Depression, such as farmers, war veterans, and the middle class.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Although Hitler had terminated his Austrian citizenship in 1925, he did not acquire German citizenship for almost seven years.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] This meant that he was stateless, legally unable to run for public office, and still faced the risk of deportation.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 February 1932, the interior minister of Brunswick, Dietrich Klagges, who was a member of the Nazi Party, appointed Hitler as administrator for the state's delegation to the Reichsrat in Berlin, making Hitler a citizen of Brunswick, and thus of Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler ran against Hindenburg in the 1932 presidential election.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] A speech to the Industry Club in Düsseldorf on 27 January 1932 won him support from many of Germany's most powerful industrialists.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg had support from various nationalist, monarchist, Catholic, and republican parties, and some Social Democrats.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler used the campaign slogan "*Hitler über Deutschland*" ("Hitler over Germany"), a reference to his political ambitions and his campaigning by aircraft.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He was one of the first politicians to use aircraft travel for campaigning and used it effectively.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler came in second in both rounds of the election, garnering more than 35 per cent of the vote in the final election.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Although he lost to Hindenburg, this election established Hitler as a strong force in German politics.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The absence of an effective government prompted two influential politicians, Franz von Papen and Alfred Hugenberg, along with several other industrialists and businessmen, to write a letter to Hindenburg.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The signers urged Hindenburg to appoint Hitler as leader of a government "independent from parliamentary parties", which could turn into a movement that would "enrapture millions of people".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hindenburg reluctantly agreed to appoint Hitler as chancellor after two further parliamentary elections—in July and November 1932—had not resulted in the formation of a majority government.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler headed a short-lived coalition government formed by the Nazi Party (which had the most seats in the Reichstag) and Hugenberg's party, the German National People's Party (DNVP).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 30 January 1933, the new cabinet was sworn in during a brief ceremony in Hindenburg's office.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Nazi Party gained three posts: Hitler was named chancellor, Wilhelm Frick Minister of the Interior, and Hermann Göring Minister of the Interior for Prussia.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler had insisted on the ministerial positions as a way to gain control over the police in much of Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] As chancellor, Hitler worked against attempts by the Nazi Party's opponents to build a majority government.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Because of the political stalemate, he asked Hindenburg to again dissolve the Reichstag, and elections were scheduled for early March.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 27 February 1933, the Reichstag building was set on fire.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Göring blamed a communist plot, as the Dutch communist Marinus van der Lubbe was found in incriminating circumstances inside the burning building.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Until the 1960s, some historians, including William L.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Shirer and Alan Bullock, thought the Nazi Party was responsible; now the view of most historians is van der Lubbe started the fire alone.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At Hitler's urging, Hindenburg responded by signing the Reichstag Fire Decree of 28 February, drafted by the Nazis, which suspended basic rights and allowed detention without trial.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The decree was permitted under Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution, which gave the president the power to take emergency measures to protect public safety and order.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Activities of the German Communist Party (KPD) were suppressed, and 4,000 KPD members were arrested.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In addition to political campaigning, the Nazi Party engaged in paramilitary violence and the spread of anti-communist propaganda, in the days preceding the election.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On election day, 6 March 1933, the Nazis’ share of the vote increased to 44%, and the party acquired the largest number of seats in parliament.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's party failed to secure an absolute majority, necessitating another coalition with the DNVP.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 21 March 1933, the new *Reichstag* was constituted with an opening ceremony at the Garrison Church in Potsdam.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] This "Day of Potsdam" was held to demonstrate unity between the Nazi movement and the old Prussian elite and military.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler appeared in a morning coat and humbly greeted Hindenburg.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] To achieve full political control despite not having an absolute majority in parliament, Hitler's government brought the *Ermächtigungsgesetz* (Enabling Act) to a vote in the newly elected *Reichstag*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act—officially titled the *Gesetz zur Behebung der Not von Volk und Reich* ("Law to Remedy the Distress of People and Reich")—gave Hitler's cabinet the power to enact laws without the consent of the Reichstag for four years.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] These laws could (with certain exceptions) deviate from the constitution.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Since it would affect the constitution, the Enabling Act required a two-thirds majority to pass.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Leaving nothing to chance, the Nazis used the provisions of the Reichstag Fire Decree to arrest all 81 Communist deputies (in spite of their virulent campaign against the party, the Nazis had allowed the KPD to contest the election) and prevent several Social Democrats from attending.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 23 March 1933, the *Reichstag* assembled at the Kroll Opera House under turbulent circumstances.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Ranks of SA men served as guards inside the building, while large groups outside, opposing the proposed legislation, shouted slogans and threats towards the arriving members of parliament.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] After Hitler verbally promised Centre party leader Ludwig Kaas that Hindenburg would retain his power of veto, Kaas announced the Centre Party would support the Enabling Act.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Act was passed by a vote of 444–94, with all parties except the Social Democrats voting in favour.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Enabling Act, along with the Reichstag Fire Decree, transformed Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Having achieved full control over the legislative and executive branches of government, Hitler and his allies began to suppress the remaining opposition.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Social Democratic Party was made illegal, and its assets were seized.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While many trade union delegates were in Berlin for May Day activities, SA stormtroopers occupied union offices around the country.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 2 May 1933, all trade unions were forced to dissolve, and their leaders were arrested.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The German Labour Front was formed as an umbrella organisation to represent all workers, administrators, and company owners, thus reflecting the concept of Nazism in the spirit of Hitler's *Volksgemeinschaft* ("people's community").
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] By the end of June, the other parties had been intimidated into disbanding.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] This included the Nazis' nominal coalition partner, the DNVP; with the SA's help, Hitler forced its leader, Hugenberg, to resign on 29 June.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 14 July 1933, the Nazi Party was declared the only legal political party in Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The demands of the SA for more political and military power caused anxiety among military, industrial, and political leaders.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In response, Hitler purged the entire SA leadership in the Night of the Long Knives, which took place from 30 June to 2 July 1934.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler targeted Ernst Röhm and other SA leaders who, along with several Hitler's political adversaries (such as Gregor Strasser and former chancellor Kurt von Schleicher), were rounded up, arrested, and shot.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While the international community and some Germans were shocked by the killings, many in Germany believed Hitler was restoring order.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On the previous day, the cabinet had enacted the Law Concerning the Head of State of the German Reich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] This law stated that upon Hindenburg's death, the office of president would be abolished, and its powers merged with those of the chancellor.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler thus became head of state as well as head of government and was formally named as *Führer und Reichskanzler* (Leader and Chancellor of the Reich), although *Reichskanzler* was eventually dropped.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] With this action, Hitler eliminated the last legal remedy by which he could be removed from office.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] As head of state, Hitler became commander-in-chief of the armed forces.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 19 August, the merger of the presidency with the chancellorship was approved by 88 per cent of the electorate voting in a plebiscite.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, Hitler used blackmail to consolidate his hold over the military by instigating the Blomberg–Fritsch affair.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler forced his War Minister, Field Marshal Werner von Blomberg, to resign by using a police dossier that showed that Blomberg's new wife had a record for prostitution.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Army commander Colonel-General Werner von Fritsch was removed after the *Schutzstaffel* (SS) produced allegations that he had engaged in a homosexual relationship.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Both men had fallen into disfavour because they objected to Hitler's demand to make the *Wehrmacht* ready for war as early as 1938.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler assumed Blomberg's title of Commander-in-Chief, thus taking personal command of the armed forces.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He replaced the Ministry of War with the *Oberkommando der Wehrmacht* (OKW), headed by General Wilhelm Keitel.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On the same day, 16 generals were stripped of their commands, and 44 more were transferred; all were suspected of not being sufficiently pro-Nazi.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] By early February 1938, 12 more generals had been removed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler took care to give his dictatorship the appearance of legality.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Many of his decrees were explicitly based on the Reichstag Fire Decree and hence on Article 48 of the Weimar Constitution.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The *Reichstag* renewed the Enabling Act twice, each time for four years.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] While elections to the *Reichstag* were still held (in 1933, 1936, and 1938), voters were presented with a single list of Nazis and pro-Nazi "guests" which received well over 90 per cent of the vote.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] These sham elections were held in far-from-secret conditions; the Nazis threatened severe reprisals against anyone who did not vote or who voted against.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1934, Hitler appointed *Reichsbank* President Hjalmar Schacht as Minister of Economics, and in the following year, as Plenipotentiary for War Economy in charge of preparing the economy for war.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Reconstruction and rearmament were financed through Mefo bills, printing money, and seizing the assets of people arrested as enemies of the state, including Jews.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The number of unemployed fell from six million in 1932 to fewer than one million in 1936.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler oversaw one of the largest infrastructure improvement campaigns in German history, leading to the construction of dams, *autobahns*, railroads, and other civil works.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Wages were slightly lower in the mid- to late 1930s compared with wages during the Weimar Republic, while the cost of living increased by 25 per cent.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The average workweek increased during the shift to a war economy; by 1939, the average German was working between 47 and 50 hours a week.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler's government sponsored architecture on an immense scale.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Albert Speer, instrumental in implementing Hitler's classicist reinterpretation of German culture, was placed in charge of the proposed architectural renovations of Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Despite a threatened multi-nation boycott, Germany hosted the 1936 Olympic Games.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler officiated at the opening ceremonies and attended events at both the Winter Games in Garmisch-Partenkirchen and the Summer Games in Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In a meeting with German military leaders on 3 February 1933, Hitler spoke of "conquest for *Lebensraum* in the East and its ruthless Germanisation" as his ultimate foreign policy objectives.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler found Bülow's goals to be too modest.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In speeches during this period, he stressed what he termed the peaceful goals of his policies and a willingness to work within international agreements.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At the first meeting of his cabinet in 1933, Hitler prioritised military spending over unemployment relief.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany withdrew from the League of Nations and the World Disarmament Conference in October 1933.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In January 1935, over 90 per cent of the people of the Saarland, then under League of Nations administration, voted to unite with Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] That March, Hitler announced an expansion of the Wehrmacht to 600,000 members—six times the number permitted by the Versailles Treaty—including development of an air force (*Luftwaffe*) and an increase in the size of the navy (*Kriegsmarine*).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, France, Italy, and the League of Nations condemned these violations of the Treaty but did nothing to stop them.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The Anglo-German Naval Agreement (AGNA) of 18 June allowed German tonnage to increase to 35 per cent of that of the Royal Navy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler called the signing of the AGNA "the happiest day of his life", believing that the agreement marked the beginning of the Anglo-German alliance he had predicted in *Mein Kampf*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] France and Italy were not consulted before the signing, directly undermining the League of Nations and setting the Treaty of Versailles on the path towards irrelevance.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Germany reoccupied the demilitarised zone in the Rhineland in March 1936, in violation of the Versailles Treaty.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler also sent troops to Spain to support Francisco Franco and his Nationalist faction during the Spanish Civil War after receiving an appeal for help in July 1936.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At the same time, Hitler continued his efforts to create an Anglo-German alliance.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In August 1936, in response to a growing economic crisis caused by his rearmament efforts, Hitler ordered Göring to implement a Four Year Plan to prepare Germany for war within the next four years.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] The plan envisaged an all-out struggle between "Judaeo-Bolshevism" and German Nazism, which in Hitler's view required a committed effort of rearmament regardless of the economic costs.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In October 1936, Count Galeazzo Ciano, foreign minister of Mussolini's government, visited Germany, where he signed a Nine-Point Protocol as an expression of *rapprochement* and had a personal meeting with Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 1 November, Mussolini declared an "axis" between Germany and Italy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] On 25 November, Germany signed the Anti-Comintern Pact with Japan.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Britain, China, Italy, and Poland were also invited to join the Anti-Comintern Pact, but only Italy signed in 1937.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler abandoned his plan of an Anglo-German alliance, blaming "inadequate" British leadership.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] At a meeting in the Reich Chancellery with his foreign ministers and military chiefs that November, Hitler restated his intention of acquiring *Lebensraum* for the German people.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He ordered preparations for war in the East to begin as early as 1938 and no later than 1943.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In the event of his death, the conference minutes, recorded as the Hossbach Memorandum, were to be regarded as his "political testament".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] He felt that a severe decline in living standards in Germany as a result of the economic crisis could only be stopped by military aggression aimed at seizing Austria and Czechoslovakia.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] Hitler urged quick action before Britain and France gained a permanent lead in the arms race.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] In early 1938, in the wake of the Blomberg–Fritsch affair, Hitler asserted control of the military-foreign policy apparatus, dismissing Neurath as foreign minister and appointing himself as War Minister.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p01] From early 1938 onwards, Hitler was carrying out a foreign policy ultimately aimed at war.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In February 1938, on the advice of his newly appointed foreign minister, the strongly pro-Japanese Joachim von Ribbentrop, Hitler ended the Sino-German alliance with the Republic of China to instead enter into an alliance with the more modern and powerful Empire of Japan.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler announced German recognition of Manchukuo, the Japanese puppet state in Manchuria, and renounced German claims to their former colonies in the Pacific held by Japan.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered an end to arms shipments to China and recalled all German officers working with the Chinese Army.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In retaliation, Chinese General Chiang Kai-shek cancelled all Sino-German economic agreements, depriving the Germans of many Chinese raw materials.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 March 1938, Hitler announced the unification of Austria with Germany in the *Anschluss*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler then turned his attention to the ethnic German population of the Sudetenland region of Czechoslovakia.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28–29 March 1938, Hitler held a series of secret meetings in Berlin with Konrad Henlein of the Sudeten German Party, the largest of the ethnic German parties of the Sudetenland.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The men agreed that Henlein would demand increased autonomy for Sudeten Germans from the Czechoslovak government, thus providing a pretext for German military action against Czechoslovakia.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In April 1938, Henlein told the foreign minister of Hungary that "whatever the Czech government might offer, he would always raise still higher demands ... he wanted to sabotage an understanding by any means because this was the only method to blow up Czechoslovakia quickly".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In private, Hitler considered the Sudeten issue unimportant; his real intention was a war of conquest against Czechoslovakia.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler ordered the OKW to prepare for *Fall Grün* (Case Green), the code name for an invasion of Czechoslovakia.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of intense French and British diplomatic pressure, on 5 September, Czechoslovak president Edvard Beneš unveiled the "Fourth Plan" for constitutional reorganisation of his country, which agreed to most of Henlein's demands for Sudeten autonomy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Henlein's party responded to Beneš's offer by instigating a series of violent clashes with the Czechoslovak police that led to the declaration of martial law in certain Sudeten districts.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany was dependent on imported oil; a confrontation with Britain over the Czechoslovak dispute could curtail Germany's oil supplies.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] This forced Hitler to call off *Fall Grün*, originally planned for 1 October 1938.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 29 September, Hitler, Neville Chamberlain, Édouard Daladier, and Mussolini attended a one-day conference in Munich that led to the Munich Agreement, which handed over the Sudetenland districts to Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Chamberlain was satisfied with the Munich conference, calling the outcome "peace for our time", while Hitler was angered about the missed opportunity for war in 1938; he expressed his disappointment in a speech on 9 October in Saarbrücken.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In Hitler's view, the British-brokered peace, although favourable to the ostensible German demands, was a diplomatic defeat which spurred his intent of limiting British power to pave the way for the eastern expansion of Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] As a result of the summit, Hitler was selected *Time* magazine's Man of the Year for 1938.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1938 and early 1939, the continuing economic crisis caused by rearmament forced Hitler to make major defence cuts.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In his "Export or die" speech of 30 January 1939, he called for an economic offensive to increase German foreign exchange holdings to pay for raw materials such as high-grade iron needed for military weapons.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 14 March 1939, under threat from Hungary, Slovakia declared independence and received protection from Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The next day, in violation of the Munich Agreement and possibly as a result of the deepening economic crisis requiring additional assets, Hitler ordered the Wehrmacht to invade the Czech rump state, and from Prague Castle he proclaimed the territory a German protectorate.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In private discussions in 1939, Hitler declared Britain the main enemy to be defeated and that Poland's obliteration was a necessary prelude for that goal.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The eastern flank would be secured, and land would be added to Germany's *Lebensraum*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Offended by the British "guarantee" on 31 March 1939 of Polish independence, he said, "I shall brew them a devil's drink".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In a speech in Wilhelmshaven for the launch of the battleship *Tirpitz* on 1 April, he threatened to denounce the Anglo-German Naval Agreement if the British continued to guarantee Polish independence, which he perceived as an "encirclement" policy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Poland was to either become a German satellite state, or it would be neutralised to secure the Reich's eastern flank and prevent a possible British blockade.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler initially favoured the idea of a satellite state, but upon its rejection by the Polish government, he decided to invade and made this the main foreign policy goal of 1939.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 3 April, Hitler ordered the military to prepare for *Fall Weiss* ("Case White"), the plan for invading Poland on 25 August.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In a Reichstag speech on 28 April, he renounced both the Anglo-German Naval Agreement and the German–Polish Non-Aggression Pact.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians such as William Carr, Gerhard Weinberg, and Ian Kershaw have argued that one reason for Hitler's rush to war was his fear of an early death.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He had repeatedly claimed that he must lead Germany into war before he got too old, as his successors might lack his strength of will.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was concerned that a military attack against Poland could result in a premature war with Britain.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's foreign minister and former Ambassador to London, Joachim von Ribbentrop, assured him that neither Britain nor France would honour its commitments to Poland.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Accordingly, on 22 August 1939, Hitler ordered a military mobilisation against Poland.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] This plan required tacit Soviet support, and the non-aggression pact (the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact) between Germany and the Soviet Union, led by Joseph Stalin, included a secret agreement to partition Poland between the two countries.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Contrary to Ribbentrop's prediction that Britain would sever Anglo-Polish ties, Britain and Poland signed the Anglo-Polish alliance on 25 August 1939.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] This, along with news from Italy that Mussolini would not honour the Pact of Steel, prompted Hitler to postpone the attack on Poland from 25 August to 1 September.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler unsuccessfully tried to manoeuvre the British into neutrality by offering them a non-aggression guarantee on 25 August; he then instructed Ribbentrop to present a last-minute peace plan with an impossibly short time limit in an effort to blame the imminent war on British and Polish inaction.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 1 September 1939, Germany invaded western Poland under the pretext of having been denied claims to the Free City of Danzig and the right to extraterritorial roads across the Polish Corridor, which Germany had ceded under the Versailles Treaty.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In response, Britain and France declared war on Germany on 3 September, surprising Hitler and prompting him to angrily ask Ribbentrop, "Now what?" Britain and France did not act on their declarations immediately, and on 17 September, Soviet forces invaded eastern Poland.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The fall of Poland was followed by what contemporary journalists dubbed the "Phoney War" or *Sitzkrieg* ("sitting war").
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler instructed the two newly appointed Gauleiters of north-western Poland, Albert Forster of Reichsgau Danzig-West Prussia and Arthur Greiser of Reichsgau Wartheland, to Germanise their areas, with "no questions asked" about how this was accomplished.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In Forster's area, ethnic Poles merely had to sign forms stating that they had German blood.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In contrast, Greiser agreed with Himmler and carried out an ethnic cleansing campaign towards Poles.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Greiser soon complained that Forster was allowing thousands of Poles to be accepted as "racial" Germans and thus endangered German "racial purity".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] This inaction has been cited as an example of the theory of "working towards the Führer", in which Hitler issued vague instructions and expected his subordinates to develop policies independently.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Another dispute pitched one side represented by Heinrich Himmler and Greiser, who championed ethnic cleansing in Poland, against another represented by Göring and Hans Frank (governor-general of occupied Poland), who called for turning Poland into the "granary" of the Reich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 12 February 1940, the dispute was initially settled in favour of the Göring–Frank view, which ended the economically disruptive mass expulsions.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 May 1940, Himmler issued a memo entitled "Some Thoughts on the Treatment of Alien Population in the East", calling for the expulsion of the entire Jewish population of Europe into Africa and the reduction of the Polish population to a "leaderless class of labourers".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler called Himmler's memo "good and correct", and, ignoring Göring and Frank, implemented the Himmler–Greiser policy in Poland.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 9 April, German forces invaded Denmark and Norway.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On the same day, Hitler proclaimed the birth of the Greater Germanic Reich, his vision of a united empire of Germanic nations of Europe in which the Dutch, Flemish, and Scandinavians were joined into a "racially pure" polity under German leadership.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In May 1940, Germany attacked France, and conquered Luxembourg, the Netherlands, and Belgium.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] These victories prompted Mussolini to have Italy join forces with Hitler on 10 June.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] France and Germany signed an armistice on 22 June.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw notes that Hitler's popularity within Germany—and German support for the war—reached its peak when he returned to Berlin on 6 July from his tour of Paris.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the unexpected swift victory, Hitler promoted 12 generals to the rank of field marshal during the 1940 Field Marshal Ceremony.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Britain, whose troops were forced to evacuate France by sea from Dunkirk, continued to fight alongside other British dominions in the Battle of the Atlantic.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler made peace overtures to the new British prime minister, Winston Churchill, and upon their rejection, he ordered a series of aerial attacks on Royal Air Force airbases and radar stations in southeast England.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 September, the systematic nightly bombing of London began.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The German Luftwaffe failed to defeat the Royal Air Force in what became known as the Battle of Britain.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By the end of September, Hitler realised that air superiority for the invasion of Britain (in Operation Sea Lion) could not be achieved, and ordered the operation postponed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The nightly air raids on British cities intensified and continued for months, including London, Plymouth, and Coventry.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 27 September 1940, the Tripartite Pact was signed in Berlin by Saburō Kurusu of Imperial Japan, Hitler, and Italian foreign minister Ciano, and later expanded to include Hungary, Romania, and Bulgaria, thus yielding the Axis powers.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's attempt to integrate the Soviet Union into the anti-British bloc failed after inconclusive talks between Hitler and Molotov in Berlin in November, and he ordered preparations for the invasion of the Soviet Union.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In early 1941, German forces were deployed to North Africa, the Balkans, and the Middle East.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In February, German forces arrived in Libya to bolster the Italian presence.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In April, Hitler launched the invasion of Yugoslavia, quickly followed by the invasion of Greece.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In May, German forces were sent to support Iraqi forces fighting against the British and to invade Crete.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 November, Hitler met in Berlin with Amin al-Husseini, the Grand Mufti of Jerusalem.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 June 1941, contravening the Molotov–Ribbentrop Pact of 1939, over three million Axis troops attacked the Soviet Union.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] This offensive (codenamed Operation Barbarossa) was intended to destroy the Soviet Union and seize its natural resources for subsequent aggression against the Western powers.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The action was also part of the overall plan to obtain more living space for German people; and Hitler thought a successful invasion would force Britain to negotiate a surrender.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The invasion conquered a huge area, including the Baltic republics, Belarus, and West Ukraine.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By early August, Axis troops had advanced 500 km (310 miles) and won the Battle of Smolensk.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Army Group Centre to temporarily halt its advance to Moscow and divert its Panzer groups to aid in the encirclement of Leningrad and Kiev.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] His generals disagreed with this change, having advanced within 400 km (250 miles) of Moscow, and his decision caused a crisis among the military leadership.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The pause provided the Red Army with an opportunity to mobilise fresh reserves; the historian Russel Stolfi considers it to be one of the major factors that caused the failure of the Moscow offensive, which was resumed in October 1941 and ended disastrously in December.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] During this crisis, Hitler appointed himself as head of the *Oberkommando des Heeres*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 7 December 1941, Japan attacked the American fleet based at Pearl Harbor, Hawaii.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Four days later, Hitler declared war against the United States.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 18 December 1941, Himmler asked Hitler, "What to do with the Jews of Russia?", to which Hitler replied, *"als Partisanen auszurotten"* ("exterminate them as partisans").
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The Israeli historian Yehuda Bauer has commented that the remark is probably as close as historians will ever get to a definitive order from Hitler for the genocide carried out during the Holocaust.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In late 1942, German forces were defeated in the Second Battle of El Alamein, thwarting Hitler's plans to seize the Suez Canal and the Middle East.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Overconfident in his own military expertise following the earlier victories in 1940, Hitler became distrustful of his Army High Command and began to interfere in military and tactical planning, with damaging consequences.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In December 1942 and January 1943, Hitler's repeated refusal to allow their withdrawal at the Battle of Stalingrad led to the near-destruction of the 6th Army.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Over 200,000 Axis soldiers were killed, and 235,000 were taken prisoner.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Thereafter came a decisive strategic defeat at the Battle of Kursk.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's military judgment became increasingly erratic, and Germany's military and economic position deteriorated, as did Hitler's health.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Following the Allied invasion of Sicily in 1943, Mussolini was removed from power by King Victor Emmanuel III after a vote of no confidence of the Grand Council of Fascism.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Marshal Pietro Badoglio, placed in charge of the government, soon surrendered to the Allies.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Throughout 1943 and 1944, the Soviet Union steadily forced Hitler's armies into retreat along the Eastern Front.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 6 June 1944, the Western Allied armies landed in northern France in one of the largest amphibious operations in history, Operation Overlord.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Many German officers concluded that defeat was inevitable and that continuing under Hitler's leadership would result in the complete destruction of the country.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Between 1939 and 1945, there were numerous plans to assassinate Hitler, some of which proceeded to significant degrees.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The most well-known and significant, the 20 July plot of 1944, came from within Germany and was at least partly driven by the increasing prospect of a German defeat in the war.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Part of Operation Valkyrie, the plot involved Claus von Stauffenberg planting a bomb in one of Hitler's headquarters, the Wolf's Lair at Rastenburg.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler narrowly survived because the staff officer Heinz Brandt moved the briefcase containing the bomb behind a leg of the heavy conference table, which deflected much of the blast.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Later, Hitler ordered reprisals, resulting in the execution of more than 4,900 people.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was put on the United Nations War Crimes Commission's first list of war criminals in December 1944, after determining that Hitler could be held criminally responsible for the acts of the Nazis in occupied countries.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By March 1945, at least seven indictments had been filed against him.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By late 1944, both the Red Army and the Western Allies were advancing into Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Recognising the strength and determination of the Red Army, Hitler decided to use his remaining mobile reserves against the American and British armies, which he perceived as far weaker.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 16 December, he launched the Ardennes Offensive to incite disunity among the Western Allies and perhaps convince them to join his fight against the Soviets.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] After some temporary successes, the offensive failed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In any case only those who are inferior will remain after this struggle, for the good have already been killed".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The same day, Hitler ordered the destruction of all German industrial infrastructure before it could fall into Allied hands.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Minister for Armaments Albert Speer was entrusted with executing this scorched earth policy, but he secretly disobeyed the order.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's hope to negotiate peace with the United States and Britain was encouraged by the death of US president Franklin D.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Roosevelt on 12 April 1945, but contrary to his expectations, this caused no rift among the Allies.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 20 April, his 56th birthday, Hitler made his last trip from the *Führerbunker* to the surface.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In the ruined garden of the Reich Chancellery, he awarded Iron Crosses to boy soldiers of the Hitler Youth, who were now fighting the Red Army at the front near Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By 21 April, Georgy Zhukov's 1st Belorussian Front had broken through the defences of General Gotthard Heinrici's Army Group Vistula during the Battle of the Seelow Heights and advanced to the outskirts of Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In denial about the dire situation, Hitler placed his hopes on the undermanned and under-equipped *Armeeabteilung Steiner* (Army Detachment Steiner), commanded by Felix Steiner.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered Steiner to attack the northern flank of the salient, while the German Ninth Army was ordered to attack northward in a pincer attack.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] During a military conference on 22 April, Hitler enquired about Steiner's offensive.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He was informed that the attack had not been launched and that the Soviets had entered Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ordered everyone but Wilhelm Keitel, Alfred Jodl, Hans Krebs, and Wilhelm Burgdorf to leave the room, then launched into a tirade against the perceived treachery and incompetence of his generals, culminating in his declaration—for the first time—that "everything is lost".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He announced that he would stay in Berlin until the end and then shoot himself.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By 23 April, the Red Army had surrounded Berlin, and Goebbels made a proclamation urging its citizens to defend the city.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] That same day, Göring sent a telegram from Berchtesgaden, arguing that as Hitler was isolated in Berlin, Göring should assume leadership of Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Göring set a deadline, after which he would consider Hitler incapacitated.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler responded by having Göring arrested, and in his last will and testament of 29 April, he removed Göring from all government positions.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 28 April, Hitler discovered that Himmler, who had left Berlin on 20 April, was attempting to negotiate a surrender to the Western Allies.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He considered this treason and ordered Himmler's arrest.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He also ordered the execution of Hermann Fegelein, Himmler's SS representative at Hitler's headquarters in Berlin, for desertion.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] After midnight on the night of 28–29 April, Hitler married Eva Braun in a small civil ceremony in the *Führerbunker*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Later that afternoon, Hitler was informed that Mussolini had been executed by the Italian resistance movement on the previous day; this is believed to have increased his determination to avoid capture.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 30 April, Soviet troops were within five hundred metres of the Reich Chancellery when Hitler shot himself in the head and Braun bit into a cyanide capsule.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In accordance with Hitler's wishes, their corpses were carried outside to the garden behind the Reich Chancellery, where they were placed in a bomb crater, doused with petrol, and set on fire as the Red Army shelling continued.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Grand Admiral Karl Dönitz and Goebbels assumed Hitler's roles as head of state and chancellor respectively.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On the evening of 1 May, Goebbels and his wife, Magda, committed suicide in the Reich Chancellery garden, after having poisoned their six children with cyanide.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The remains of the Goebbels family, General Hans Krebs (who had committed suicide that day), and Hitler's dog Blondi were repeatedly buried and exhumed by the Soviets.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's and Braun's remains were alleged to have been moved as well, but this is most likely Soviet disinformation.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] There is no evidence that any identifiable remains of Hitler or Braun—with the exception of dental bridges—were ever found by them.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] While news of Hitler's death spread quickly, a death certificate was not issued until 1956, after a lengthy investigation to collect testimony from 42 witnesses.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's death was entered as an assumption of death based on this testimony.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The Holocaust and Germany's war in the East were based on Hitler's long-standing view that the Jews were the enemy of the German people, and that *Lebensraum* was needed for Germany's expansion.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He focused on Eastern Europe for this expansion, aiming to defeat Poland and the Soviet Union and then removing or killing the Jews and Slavs.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The *Generalplan Ost* (General Plan East) called for deporting the population of occupied Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union to West Siberia, for use as slave labour or to be murdered; the conquered territories were to be colonised by German or "Germanised" settlers.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The goal was to implement this plan after the conquest of the Soviet Union, but when this failed, Hitler moved the plans forward.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By January 1942, he had decided that the Jews, Slavs, and other deportees considered undesirable should be killed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The genocide was organised and executed by Heinrich Himmler and Reinhard Heydrich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The records of the Wannsee Conference, held on 20 January 1942 and led by Heydrich, with 15 senior Nazi officials participating, provide the clearest evidence of systematic planning for the Holocaust.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 22 February, Hitler was recorded saying, "we shall regain our health only by eliminating the Jews".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Similarly, at a meeting in July 1941 with leading functionaries of the Eastern territories, Hitler said that the easiest way to quickly pacify the areas would be best achieved by "shooting everyone who even looks odd".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Although no direct order from Hitler authorising the mass killings has surfaced, his public speeches, orders to his generals, and the diaries of Nazi officials demonstrate that he conceived and authorised the extermination of European Jewry.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] During the war, Hitler repeatedly stated his prophecy of 1939 was being fulfilled, namely, that a world war would bring about the annihilation of the Jewish race.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler approved the *Einsatzgruppen*—killing squads that followed the German army through Poland, the Baltic, and the Soviet Union—and was well informed about their activities.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] By summer 1942, Auschwitz concentration camp was expanded to accommodate large numbers of deportees for murder or enslavement.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Scores of other concentration camps and satellite camps were set up throughout Europe, with several camps devoted exclusively to extermination.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The victims were killed in concentration and extermination camps and in ghettos, and through mass shootings.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Many victims of the Holocaust were murdered in gas chambers or shot, while others died of starvation or disease or while working as slave labourers.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition to eliminating Jews, the Nazis planned to reduce the population of the conquered territories by 30 million people through starvation in an action called the Hunger Plan.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Food supplies would be diverted to the German army and German civilians.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Cities would be razed, and the land allowed to return to forest or resettled by German colonists.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Together, the Hunger Plan and *Generalplan Ost* would have led to the starvation of 80 million people in the Soviet Union.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] These partially fulfilled plans resulted in additional deaths, bringing the total number of civilians and prisoners of war who died in the democide to an estimated 19.3 million people.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies resulted in the killing of nearly two million non-Jewish Polish civilians, over three million Soviet prisoners of war, communists and other political opponents, homosexuals, the physically and mentally disabled, Jehovah's Witnesses, Adventists, and trade unionists.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler never spoke publicly about the killings and seems to have never visited the concentration camps.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The Nazis embraced the concept of racial hygiene.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] On 15 September 1935, Hitler presented two laws—known as the Nuremberg Laws—to the Reichstag.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws banned sexual relations and marriages between Aryans and Jews and were later extended to include "Gypsies, Negroes or their bastard offspring".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The laws stripped all non-Aryans of their German citizenship and forbade the employment of non-Jewish women under the age of 45 in Jewish households.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's early eugenic policies targeted children with physical and developmental disabilities in a programme dubbed Action Brandt, and he later authorised a euthanasia programme for adults with serious mental and physical disabilities, now referred to as *Aktion T4*.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler ruled the Nazi Party autocratically by asserting the *Führerprinzip* (leader principle).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The principle relied on absolute obedience of all subordinates to their superiors; thus, he viewed the government structure as a pyramid, with himself—the infallible leader—at the apex.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Rank in the party was not determined by elections—positions were filled through appointment by those of higher rank, who demanded unquestioning obedience to the will of the leader.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership style was to give contradictory orders to his subordinates and to place them into positions where their duties and responsibilities overlapped with those of others, to have "the stronger one [do] the job".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In this way, Hitler fostered distrust, competition, and infighting among his subordinates to consolidate and maximise his own power.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] His cabinet never met after 1938, and he discouraged his ministers from meeting independently.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler typically did not give written orders; instead, he communicated verbally, or had them conveyed through his close associate Martin Bormann.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He entrusted Bormann with his paperwork, appointments, and personal finances; Bormann used his position to control the flow of information and access to Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler dominated his country's war effort during World War II to a greater extent than any other national leader.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He strengthened his control of the armed forces in 1938, and subsequently made all major decisions regarding Germany's military strategy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] His decision to mount a risky series of offensives against Norway, France, and the Low Countries in 1940, against the advice of the military, proved successful, though the diplomatic and military strategies he employed in attempts to force the United Kingdom out of the war ended in failure.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler deepened his involvement in the war effort by appointing himself commander-in-chief of the Army in December 1941; from this point forward, he personally directed the war against the Soviet Union, while his military commanders facing the Western Allies retained a degree of autonomy.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's leadership became increasingly disconnected from reality as the war turned against Germany, with the military's defensive strategies often hindered by his slow decision-making and frequent directives to hold untenable positions.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Nevertheless, he continued to believe that only his leadership could deliver victory.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In the final months of the war, Hitler refused to consider peace negotiations, regarding the destruction of Germany as preferable to surrender.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The military did not challenge Hitler's dominance of the war effort, and senior officers generally supported and enacted his decisions.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler created a public image as a celibate man without a domestic life, dedicated entirely to his political mission and the nation.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He met his lover, Eva Braun, in 1929, and married her on 29 April 1945, one day before they both committed suicide.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In September 1931, his half-niece, Geli Raubal, committed suicide with Hitler's gun in his Munich apartment.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] It was rumoured among contemporaries that Geli was in a romantic relationship with him, and her death was a source of deep, lasting pain.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Paula Hitler, the younger sister of Hitler and the last living member of his immediate family, died in June 1960.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was born to a practising Catholic mother and an anti-clerical father; after leaving home, Hitler never again attended Mass or received the sacraments.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Albert Speer stated that Hitler railed against the church to his political associates, and though he never officially left the church, he had no attachment to it.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer added that Hitler felt that in the absence of organised religion, people would turn to mysticism, which he considered regressive.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Speer, Hitler believed that Japanese religious beliefs or Islam would have been a more suitable religion for Germans than Christianity, with its "meekness and flabbiness".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Conway states that Hitler was fundamentally opposed to the Christian churches.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler did not believe in God, was anticlerical, and held Christian ethics in contempt because they contravened his preferred view of "survival of the fittest".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He favoured aspects of Protestantism that suited his own views, and adopted some elements of the Catholic Church's hierarchical organisation, liturgy, and phraseology.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In a 1932 speech, Hitler stated that he was not a Catholic, and declared himself a German Christian.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler viewed the church as an important politically conservative influence on society, and he adopted a strategic relationship with it that "suited his immediate political purposes".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In public, Hitler often praised Christian heritage and German Christian culture, though professing a belief in an "Aryan Jesus" who fought against the Jews.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] However, in *Hitler’s Table Talk* he was recorded as saying Christianity was an "absurdity" and nonsense founded on lies.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] According to a US Office of Strategic Services (OSS) report, "The Nazi Master Plan", Hitler planned to destroy the influence of Christian churches within the Reich.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Shirer commented that "the Nazi regime intended to destroy Christianity in Germany, if it could, and substitute the old paganism of the early tribal Germanic gods with the new paganism of the Nazi extremists".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] According to Bullock, Hitler wanted to wait until after the war before executing this plan.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Richard Steigmann-Gall has concluded there was no firm evidence of such a plan to replace Christianity.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Swedish historian Mikael Nilsson notes that many of Hitler's religious statements are sourced from *Table Talk*, which he considers highly unreliable: much of the content was written days after the event and was heavily modified to suit the agendas of Martin Bormann and later François Genoud.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer wrote that Hitler had a negative view of Himmler's and Alfred Rosenberg's mystical notions and Himmler's attempt to mythologise the SS.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler was more pragmatic, and his ambitions centred on more practical concerns.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Researchers have variously suggested that Hitler suffered from irritable bowel syndrome, skin lesions, irregular heartbeat, coronary sclerosis, Parkinson's disease, syphilis, giant-cell arteritis, tinnitus, and monorchism.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In a report prepared for the OSS in 1943, Walter Charles Langer of Harvard University described Hitler as a "neurotic psychopath" and speculated that he exhibited masochistic tendencies and deep feelings of self-loathing, which he projected onto others, particularly Jews.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In his 1977 book *The Psychopathic God: Adolf Hitler*, the historian Robert G.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Waite proposes that Hitler suffered from borderline personality disorder.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The historians Henrik Eberle and Hans-Joachim Neumann consider that while he suffered from several illnesses, including Parkinson's disease, Hitler did not experience pathological delusions and was always fully aware of, and therefore responsible for, his decisions.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Sometime in the 1930s, Hitler adopted a mainly vegetarian diet, avoiding all meat and fish from 1942 onwards.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] At social events, he sometimes gave graphic accounts of the slaughter of animals in an effort to make his guests shun meat.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Bormann had a greenhouse constructed near the Berghof (near Berchtesgaden) to ensure a steady supply of fresh fruit and vegetables for Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler stopped drinking alcohol around the time he became vegetarian and thereafter only very occasionally drank beer or wine on social occasions.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He was a non-smoker for most of his adult life, but smoked heavily in his youth (25 to 40 cigarettes a day); he eventually quit, calling the habit "a waste of money".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He encouraged his close associates to quit by offering a gold watch to anyone able to break the habit.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler began using amphetamine occasionally after 1937 and became addicted to it in late 1942.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Speer linked this use of amphetamine to Hitler's increasingly erratic behaviour and inflexible decision-making (for example, rarely allowing military retreats).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Prescribed 90 medications during the war years by his personal physician, Theodor Morell, Hitler took many pills each day for chronic stomach problems and other ailments.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He regularly consumed amphetamine, barbiturates, opiates, and cocaine, as well as potassium bromide and atropa belladonna (the latter in the form of Doktor Koster's Antigaspills).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He suffered ruptured eardrums as a result of the 20 July plot bomb blast in 1944, and 200 wood splinters had to be removed from his legs.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Newsreel footage of Hitler shows tremors in his left hand and a shuffling walk, which began before the war and worsened towards the end of his life.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Ernst-Günther Schenck and several other doctors who met Hitler in the last weeks of his life also formed a diagnosis of Parkinson's disease.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian Joachim Fest, Hitler's suicide was likened by numerous contemporaries to a "spell" being broken.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] According to the historian John Toland, Nazism "burst like a bubble" without its leader.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Kershaw describes Hitler as "the embodiment of modern political evil".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] "Never in history has such ruination—physical and moral—been associated with the name of one man", he adds.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's political programme brought about a world war, leaving behind a devastated and impoverished Eastern and Central Europe.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Germany suffered wholesale destruction, characterised as *Stunde Null* (Zero Hour).
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler's policies inflicted human suffering on an unprecedented scale; according to R.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Rummel, the Nazi regime was responsible for the democidal killing of an estimated 19.3 million civilians and prisoners of war.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In addition, 28.7 million soldiers and civilians died as a result of military action in the European theatre of World War II.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The number of civilians killed during the Second World War was unprecedented in the history of warfare.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Historians, philosophers, and politicians often use the word "evil" to describe the Nazi regime.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Many European countries have criminalised both the promotion of Nazism and Holocaust denial.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Friedrich Meinecke described Hitler as "one of the great examples of the singular and incalculable power of personality in historical life".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The English historian Hugh Trevor-Roper saw him as "among the 'terrible simplifiers' of history, the most systematic, the most historical, the most philosophical, and yet the coarsest, cruelest, least magnanimous conqueror the world has ever known".
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Roberts, Hitler's defeat marked the end of a phase of European history dominated by Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] In its place emerged the Cold War, a global confrontation between the Western Bloc, dominated by the United States and other NATO nations, and the Eastern Bloc, dominated by the Soviet Union.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] The historian Sebastian Haffner asserted that without Hitler and the displacement of the Jews, the modern nation-state of Israel would not exist.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He contends that without Hitler, the de-colonisation of former European spheres of influence would have been postponed.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Further, Haffner claimed that other than Alexander the Great, Hitler had a more significant impact than any other comparable historical figure, in that he too caused a wide range of worldwide changes in a relatively short time span.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] Hitler exploited documentary films and newsreels to inspire a cult of personality.
[src:technocracy-movement/adolf-hitler-p02] He was involved and appeared in a series of propaganda films throughout his political career, many made by Leni Riefenstahl, regarded as a pioneer of modern filmmaking.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] Born as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg, part of the German Empire, Einstein moved to Switzerland in 1895, forsaking his citizenship the following year.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1896, at the age of seventeen, he enrolled in the mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the Swiss federal polytechnic school in Zurich, graduating in 1900.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] He acquired Swiss citizenship a year later, which he kept for the rest of his life, and afterwards secured a permanent position at the Swiss Patent Office in Bern.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, he submitted a successful PhD dissertation to the University of Zurich.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1914, he moved to Berlin to join the Prussian Academy of Sciences and the Humboldt University of Berlin, becoming director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics in 1917; he also became a Prussian and consequently also German citizen again.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1933, while Einstein was visiting the United States, Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] Horrified by the Nazi persecution of his fellow Jews, he decided to remain in the US, and was granted American citizenship in 1940.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] On the eve of World War II, he endorsed a letter to President Franklin D.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] Roosevelt alerting him to the potential German nuclear weapons program and recommending that the US begin similar research, later carried out as the Manhattan Project.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, sometimes described as his *annus mirabilis* (miracle year), he published four groundbreaking papers.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In them, he outlined a theory of the photoelectric effect, explained Brownian motion, introduced his special theory of relativity, and demonstrated that if the special theory is correct, mass and energy are equivalent to each other.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1915, he proposed a general theory of relativity that extended his system of mechanics to incorporate gravitation.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] A paper that he published the following year laid out the implications of general relativity for the modeling of the structure and evolution of the universe as a whole.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] It introduced the cosmological constant and is further regarded as the first step in the field of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In the middle part of his career, Einstein made important contributions to statistical mechanics and quantum theory.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] Especially notable was his work on the quantum physics of radiation, in which light consists of particles, subsequently called photons.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] With physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, he laid the groundwork for Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] For much of the last phase of his academic life, Einstein worked on two endeavors that ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] First, he advocated against quantum theory's introduction of fundamental randomness into science's picture of the world, objecting that "God does not play dice".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] Second, he attempted to devise a unified field theory by generalizing his geometric theory of gravitation to include electromagnetism.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] As a result, he became increasingly isolated from mainstream modern physics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] Many things are named after him, including the element Einsteinium.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p01] In 1999, he was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was born in Ulm as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg in the German Empire on 14 March 1879.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His parents, secular Ashkenazi Jews, were Hermann Einstein, a salesman and engineer, and Pauline Koch.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1880, the family moved to Munich's borough of Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, where Einstein's father and his uncle Jakob founded Elektrotechnische Fabrik J.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein & Cie, a company that manufactured electrical equipment based on direct current.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] When he was very young, his parents worried that he had a learning disability because he was very slow to learn to talk.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] When he was five and sick in bed, his father brought him a compass.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] This sparked his lifelong fascination with electromagnetism.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Peter's Catholic elementary school in Munich from the age of five.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] When he was eight, he was transferred to the Luitpold Gymnasium, where he received advanced primary and then secondary school education.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1894, Hermann and Jakob's company tendered for a contract to install electric lighting in Munich, but without success—they lacked the capital that would have been required to update their technology from direct current to the more efficient, alternating current alternative.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The failure of their bid forced them to sell their Munich factory and search for new opportunities elsewhere.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The Einstein family moved to Italy, first to Milan and a few months later to Pavia, where they settled in Palazzo Cornazzani.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein, then fifteen, stayed behind in Munich in order to finish his schooling.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His father wanted him to study electrical engineering, but he was a fractious pupil who found the Gymnasium's regimen and teaching methods far from congenial.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He later wrote that the school's policy of strict rote learning was harmful to creativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] At the end of December 1894, a letter from a doctor persuaded the Luitpold's authorities to release him from its care, and he joined his family in Pavia.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] While in Italy as a teenager, he wrote an essay titled "On the Investigation of the State of the Ether in a Magnetic Field".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein excelled at physics and mathematics from an early age, and soon acquired the mathematical expertise normally only found in a child several years his senior.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He began teaching himself algebra, calculus and Euclidean geometry when he was twelve; he made such rapid progress that he discovered an original proof of the Pythagorean theorem before his thirteenth birthday.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] A family tutor, Max Talmud, said that only a short time after he had given the twelve year old Einstein a geometry textbook, the boy "had worked through the whole book.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He thereupon devoted himself to higher mathematics ...
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Soon the flight of his mathematical genius was so high I could not follow." Einstein recorded that he had "mastered integral and differential calculus" while still just fourteen.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His love of algebra and geometry was so great that at twelve, he was already confident that nature could be understood as a "mathematical structure".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] At thirteen, when his range of enthusiasms had broadened to include music and philosophy, Talmud introduced Einstein to Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1895, at the age of sixteen, Einstein sat the entrance examination for the federal polytechnic school (later the Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule, ETH) in Zurich, Switzerland.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He failed to reach the required standard in the general part of the test, but performed with distinction in physics and mathematics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] On the advice of the polytechnic's principal, he completed his secondary education at the Argovian cantonal school (a gymnasium) in Aarau, Switzerland, graduating in 1896.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] While lodging in Aarau with the family of Jost Winteler, he fell in love with Winteler's daughter, Marie.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In January 1896, with his father's approval, Einstein renounced his citizenship of the German Kingdom of Württemberg in order to avoid conscription into military service.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The *Matura* (graduation for the successful completion of higher secondary schooling), awarded to him in September 1896, acknowledged him to have performed well across most of the curriculum, allotting him a top grade of 6 for history, physics, algebra, geometry, and descriptive geometry.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] At seventeen, he enrolled in the four-year mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the federal polytechnic school.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He befriended fellow student Marcel Grossmann, who would help him there to get by despite his loose study habits, and later to mathematically underpin his revolutionary insights into physics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Marie Winteler, a year older than him, took up a teaching post in Olsberg, Switzerland.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The five other polytechnic school freshmen following the same course as Einstein included just one woman, a twenty year old Serbian, Mileva Marić.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Over the next few years, the pair spent many hours discussing their shared interests and learning about topics in physics that the polytechnic school's lectures did not cover.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In his letters to Marić, Einstein confessed that exploring science with her by his side was much more enjoyable than reading a textbook in solitude.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually the two students became not only friends, but also lovers.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Historians of physics are divided on the question of the extent to which Marić contributed to the insights of Einstein's *annus mirabilis* publications.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] There is at least some evidence that he was influenced by her scientific ideas, but there are scholars who doubt whether her impact on his thought was of any great significance at all.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Correspondence between Einstein and Marić, discovered and published in 1987, revealed that the couple had a daughter named Lieserl.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] She was born in early 1902 while Marić was visiting her parents in Novi Sad.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić returned to Switzerland the child was no longer with her.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In a letter written in September 1903, Einstein suggested that the girl was either given up for adoption or died of scarlet fever in infancy.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić married in January 1903.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In May 1904, their son Hans Albert was born in Bern, Switzerland.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Their son Eduard was born in Zurich in July 1910.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1912, Einstein entered into a relationship with Elsa Löwenthal, who was both his first cousin on his mother's side and his second cousin on his father's.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić learned of his infidelity soon after moving to Berlin with him in April 1914, she returned to Zurich, taking Hans Albert and Eduard with her.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić were granted a divorce on 14 February 1919 on the grounds of having lived apart for five years.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] As part of the divorce settlement, Einstein agreed that if he were to win a Nobel Prize, he would give the money that he received to Marić; he won the prize two years later.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1923, he began a relationship with a secretary named Betty Neumann, the niece of his close friend Hans Mühsam.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Löwenthal nevertheless remained loyal to him, accompanying him when he emigrated to the United States in 1933.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1935, she was diagnosed with heart and kidney problems.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] A volume of Einstein's letters released by the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 2006 added some other women with whom he was romantically involved.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] They included Margarete Lebach (a married Austrian), Estella Katzenellenbogen (the rich owner of a florist business), Toni Mendel (a wealthy Jewish widow) and Ethel Michanowski (a Berlin socialite), with whom he spent time and from whom he accepted gifts while married to Löwenthal.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] After being widowed, Einstein was briefly in a relationship with Margarita Konenkova, thought by some to be a Russian spy; her husband, the Russian sculptor Sergei Konenkov, created the bronze bust of Einstein at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Following an episode of acute mental illness at about the age of twenty, Einstein's son Eduard was diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He spent the remainder of his life either in the care of his mother or in temporary confinement in an asylum.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] After her death, he was committed permanently to Burghölzli, the Psychiatric University Hospital in Zurich.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein graduated from the federal polytechnic school in 1900, duly certified as competent to teach mathematics and physics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His successful acquisition of Swiss citizenship in February 1901 was not followed by the usual sequel of conscription; the Swiss authorities deemed him medically unfit for military service.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He found that Swiss schools too appeared to have no use for him, failing to offer him a teaching position despite the almost two years that he spent applying for one.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually it was with the help of Marcel Grossmann's father that he secured a post in Bern at the Swiss Patent Office, as an assistant examiner – level III.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Patent applications that landed on Einstein's desk for his evaluation included ideas for a gravel sorter and an electric typewriter.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His employers were pleased enough with his work to make his position permanent in 1903, although they did not think that he should be promoted until he had "fully mastered machine technology".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] It is conceivable that his labors at the patent office had a bearing on his development of his special theory of relativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He arrived at his revolutionary ideas about space, time and light through thought experiments about the transmission of signals and the synchronization of clocks, matters which also figured in some of the inventions submitted to him for assessment.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1902, Einstein and his friends Conrad Habicht and Maurice Solovine, whom he had met in Bern, formed a group that held regular meetings to discuss science and philosophy.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Their choice of a name for their club, the Olympia Academy, was an ironic comment upon its far from Olympian status.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Sometimes they were joined by Marić, who limited her participation in their proceedings to careful listening.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The thinkers whose works they reflected upon included Henri Poincaré, Ernst Mach and David Hume, all of whom significantly influenced Einstein's own subsequent ideas and beliefs.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's first paper, "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen" ("Conclusions drawn from the phenomena of capillarity"), in which he proposed a model of intermolecular attraction that he afterwards disavowed as worthless, was published in the journal *Annalen der Physik* in 1901.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His 24-page doctoral dissertation also addressed a topic in molecular physics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Titled "Eine neue Bestimmung der Moleküldimensionen" ("A New Determination of Molecular Dimensions") and dedicated "Meinem Freunde Herr Dr.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Marcel Grossmann gewidmet" (to his friend Marcel Grossman), it was completed on 30 April 1905 and approved by Professor Alfred Kleiner of the University of Zurich three months later.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The publications deeply impressed Einstein's contemporaries.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's sabbatical as a civil servant approached its end in 1908, when he secured a junior teaching position at the University of Bern.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1909, a lecture on relativistic electrodynamics that he gave at the University of Zurich, much admired by Alfred Kleiner, led to Zurich's luring him away from Bern with a newly created associate professorship.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Promotion to a full professorship followed in April 1911, when he took up a chair at the German Charles-Ferdinand University in Prague, a move which required him to become an Austrian citizen of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was not completed.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His time in Prague saw him producing eleven research papers.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] From 30 October to 3 November 1911, Einstein attended the first Solvay Conference on Physics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1912, he returned to his *alma mater*, the ETH Zurich, to take up a chair in theoretical physics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His teaching activities there centered on thermodynamics and analytical mechanics, and his research interests included the molecular theory of heat, continuum mechanics and the development of a relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In his work on the latter topic, he was assisted by his friend Marcel Grossmann, whose knowledge of the kind of mathematics required was greater than his own.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In the spring of 1913, two German visitors, Max Planck and Walther Nernst, called upon Einstein in Zurich in the hope of persuading him to relocate to Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Their invitation was all the more appealing to him because Berlin happened to be the home of his latest girlfriend, Elsa Löwenthal.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He duly joined the Academy on 24 July 1913, and moved into an apartment in the Berlin district of Dahlem on 1 April 1914.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He was installed in his Humboldt University position shortly thereafter.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] The outbreak of the First World War in July 1914 marked the beginning of Einstein's gradual estrangement from the nation of his birth.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] However, this expression of his doubts about German policy did not prevent him from being elected to a two-year term as president of the German Physical Society in 1916.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] When the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics opened its doors the following year—its foundation delayed because of the war—Einstein was appointed its first director, just as Planck and Nernst had promised.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1920, and a Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1921.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Bose derived the Planck spectrum in 1924.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] That same year, Einstein was elected an International Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Britain's closest equivalent of the Nobel award, the Royal Society's Copley Medal, was not hung around Einstein's neck until 1925.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1930.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein resigned from the Prussian Academy in March 1933.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His accomplishments in Berlin had included the completion of the general theory of relativity, proving the Einstein–de Haas effect, contributing to the quantum theory of radiation, and the development of Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1911, he first calculated the gravitational deflection of light passing close to the Sun, a prediction later adjusted upon completion of the general theory of relativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He reworked his calculation in 1913, having now found a way to model gravitation with the Riemann curvature tensor of a non-Euclidean four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] A total eclipse of the Sun that took place on 29 May 1919 provided an opportunity to put his theory of gravitational lensing to the test, and observations performed by Sir Arthur Eddington yielded results that were consistent with his calculations.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Eddington's work was reported at length in newspapers around the world.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] On 7 November 1919, for example, the leading British newspaper, *The Times*, printed a banner headline that read: "Revolution in Science – New Theory of the Universe – Newtonian Ideas Overthrown".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein began his new life as an intellectual icon in America, where he arrived on 2 April 1921.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He was welcomed to New York City by Mayor John Francis Hylan, and then spent three weeks giving lectures and attending receptions.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He spoke several times at Columbia University and Princeton, and in Washington, he visited the White House with representatives of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He returned to Europe via London, where he was the guest of the philosopher and statesman Viscount Haldane.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He used his time in the British capital to meet several people prominent in British scientific, political or intellectual life, and to deliver a lecture at King's College.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1921, he published an essay, "My First Impression of the U.S.A.", in which he sought to sketch the American character.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He wrote of his transatlantic hosts in highly approving terms: "What strikes a visitor is the joyous, positive attitude to life ...
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, Einstein's travels were to the old world rather than the new.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He devoted six months to a tour of Asia that saw him speaking in Japan, Singapore and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon).
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] After his first public lecture in Tokyo, he met Emperor Yoshihito and his wife at the Imperial Palace, with thousands of spectators thronging the streets in the hope of catching a glimpse of him.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] (In a letter to his sons, he wrote that Japanese people seemed to him to be generally modest, intelligent and considerate, and to have a true appreciation of art.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] But his picture of them in his diary was less flattering: "[the] intellectual needs of this nation seem to be weaker than their artistic ones – natural disposition?" His journal also contains views of China and India which were uncomplimentary.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Of Chinese people, he wrote that "even the children are spiritless and look obtuse...
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] It would be a pity if these Chinese supplant all other races.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] For the likes of us the mere thought is unspeakably dreary".) He was greeted with even greater enthusiasm on the last leg of his tour, in which he spent twelve days in Mandatory Palestine, newly entrusted to British rule by the League of Nations in the aftermath of the First World War.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Sir Herbert Samuel, the British High Commissioner, welcomed him with a degree of ceremony normally only accorded to a visiting head of state, including a cannon salute.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] One reception held in his honor was stormed by people determined to hear him speak: he told them that he was happy that Jews were beginning to be recognized as a force in the world.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] On April 6, 1922, during a visit to Paris, Einstein engaged in a debate on relativity with the philosopher Henri Bergson.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] This dispute has had widespread ramifications for the humanities and was an academic *cause célèbre* at the time.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's decision to tour the eastern hemisphere in 1922 meant that he was unable to go to Stockholm in the December of that year to participate in the Nobel prize ceremony.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His place at the traditional Nobel banquet was taken by a German diplomat, who gave a speech praising him not only as a physicist but also as a campaigner for peace.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] A two-week visit to Spain that he undertook in 1923 saw him collecting another award, a membership of the Spanish Academy of Sciences signified by a diploma handed to him by King Alfonso XIII.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] He was appointed as a German delegate rather than as a representative of Switzerland because of the machinations of two Catholic activists, Oskar Halecki and Giuseppe Motta.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] By persuading Secretary General Eric Drummond to deny Einstein the place on the committee reserved for a Swiss thinker, they created an opening for Gonzague de Reynold, who used his League of Nations position as a platform from which to promote traditional Catholic doctrine.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's former physics professor Hendrik Lorentz and the Polish chemist Marie Curie were also members of the committee.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In March and April 1925, Einstein and his wife visited South America, where they spent about a week in Brazil, a week in Uruguay and a month in Argentina.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] In December 1930, Einstein began another significant sojourn in the United States, drawn back to the US by the offer of a two month research fellowship at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Caltech supported him in his wish that he should not be exposed to quite as much attention from the media as he had experienced when visiting the US in 1921, and he therefore declined all the invitations to receive prizes or make speeches that his admirers poured down upon him.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] But he remained willing to allow his fans at least some of the time with him that they requested.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] After arriving in New York City, Einstein was taken to various places and events, including Chinatown, a lunch with the editors of *The New York Times*, and a performance of *Carmen* at the Metropolitan Opera, where he was cheered by the audience on his arrival.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] During the days following, he was given the keys to the city by Mayor Jimmy Walker and met Nicholas Murray Butler, the president of Columbia University, who described Einstein as "the ruling monarch of the mind".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Harry Emerson Fosdick, pastor at New York's Riverside Church, gave Einstein a tour of the church and showed him a full-size statue that the church made of Einstein, standing at the entrance.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Also during his stay in New York, he joined a crowd of 15,000 people at Madison Square Garden during a Hanukkah celebration.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein next traveled to California, where he met Caltech president and Nobel laureate Robert A.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] His friendship with Millikan was "awkward", as Millikan "had a penchant for patriotic militarism", where Einstein was a pronounced pacifist.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] During an address to Caltech's students, Einstein noted that science was often inclined to do more harm than good.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] This aversion to war also led Einstein to befriend author Upton Sinclair and film star Charlie Chaplin, both noted for their pacifism.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Carl Laemmle, head of Universal Studios, gave Einstein a tour of his studio and introduced him to Chaplin.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] They had an instant rapport, with Chaplin inviting Einstein and his wife, Elsa, to his home for dinner.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin said Einstein's outward persona, calm and gentle, seemed to conceal a "highly emotional temperament", from which came his "extraordinary intellectual energy".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin's film *City Lights* was to premiere a few days later in Hollywood, and Chaplin invited Einstein and Elsa to join him as his special guests.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Walter Isaacson, Einstein's biographer, described this as "one of the most memorable scenes in the new era of celebrity".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin visited Einstein at his home on a later trip to Berlin and recalled his "modest little flat" and the piano at which he had begun writing his theory.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin speculated that it was "possibly used as kindling wood by the Nazis".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein and Chaplin were cheered at the premiere of the film.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In February 1933, while on a visit to the United States, Einstein knew he could not return to Germany with the rise to power of the Nazis under Germany's new chancellor, Adolf Hitler.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] While at American universities in early 1933, he undertook his third two-month visiting professorship at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In February and March 1933, the Gestapo repeatedly raided his family's apartment in Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He and his wife Elsa returned to Europe in March, and during the trip, they learned that the German Reichstag had passed the Enabling Act on 23 March, transforming Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship, and that they would not be able to proceed to Berlin.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Later on, they heard that their cottage had been raided by the Nazis and Einstein's personal sailboat confiscated.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Upon landing in Antwerp, Belgium on 28 March, Einstein immediately went to the German consulate and surrendered his passport, formally renouncing his German citizenship.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The renunciation was at first refused, but the Nazi government finally revoked his citizenship on 24 March 1934.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The Nazis later sold his boat and converted his cottage into a Hitler Youth camp.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In April 1933, Einstein discovered that the new German government had passed laws barring Jews from holding any official positions, including teaching at universities.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Historian Gerald Holton describes how, with "virtually no audible protest being raised by their colleagues", thousands of Jewish scientists were suddenly forced to give up their university positions and their names were removed from the rolls of institutions where they were employed.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In a subsequent letter to physicist and friend Max Born, who had already emigrated from Germany to England, Einstein wrote, "...
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was now without a permanent home, unsure where he would live and work, and equally worried about the fate of countless other scientists still in Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Aided by the Academic Assistance Council, founded in April 1933 by British Liberal politician William Beveridge to help academics escape Nazi persecution, Einstein was able to leave Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He rented a house in De Haan, Belgium, where he lived for a few months.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In late July 1933, he visited England for about six weeks at the invitation of the British Member of Parliament Commander Oliver Locker-Lampson, who had become friends with him in the preceding years.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson invited him to stay near his Cromer home in a secluded wooden cabin on Roughton Heath in the Parish of Roughton, Norfolk.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] To protect Einstein, Locker-Lampson had two bodyguards watch over him; a photo of them carrying shotguns and guarding Einstein was published in the *Daily Herald* on 24 July 1933.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson took Einstein to meet Winston Churchill at his home, and later, Austen Chamberlain and former Prime Minister Lloyd George.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein asked them to help bring Jewish scientists out of Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] British historian Martin Gilbert notes that Churchill responded immediately, and sent his friend physicist Frederick Lindemann to Germany to seek out Jewish scientists and place them in British universities.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Churchill later observed that as a result of Germany having driven the Jews out, they had lowered their "technical standards" and put the Allies' technology ahead of theirs.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein later contacted leaders of other nations, including Turkey's Prime Minister, İsmet İnönü, to whom he wrote in September 1933, requesting placement of unemployed German-Jewish scientists.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] As a result of Einstein's letter, Jewish invitees to Turkey eventually totaled over "1,000 saved individuals".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson also submitted a bill to parliament to extend British citizenship to Einstein, during which period Einstein made a number of public appearances describing the crisis brewing in Europe.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In one of his speeches he denounced Germany's treatment of Jews, while at the same time he introduced a bill promoting Jewish citizenship in Palestine, as they were being denied citizenship elsewhere.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In his speech he described Einstein as a "citizen of the world" who should be offered a temporary shelter in the UK.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Both bills failed, however, and Einstein then accepted an earlier offer from the Institute for Advanced Study, in Princeton, New Jersey, US, to become a resident scholar.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] On 3 October 1933, Einstein delivered a speech on the importance of academic freedom before a packed audience at the Royal Albert Hall in London, with *The Times* reporting he was wildly cheered throughout.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Four days later he returned to the US and took up a position at the Institute for Advanced Study, noted for having become a refuge for scientists fleeing Nazi Germany.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] At the time, most American universities, including Harvard, Princeton and Yale, had minimal or no Jewish faculty or students, as a result of their Jewish quotas, which lasted until the late 1940s.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was still undecided about his future.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's affiliation with the Institute for Advanced Study would last until his death in 1955.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He was one of the four first selected (along with John von Neumann, Kurt Gödel and Hermann Weyl) at the new Institute.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He soon developed a close friendship with Gödel; the two would take long walks together discussing their work.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Bruria Kaufman, his assistant, later became a physicist.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] During this period, Einstein tried to develop a unified field theory and to refute the accepted interpretation of quantum physics, both unsuccessfully.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He lived in Princeton at his home from 1935 onwards.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The Albert Einstein House was made a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In 1939, a group of Hungarian scientists that included émigré physicist Leó Szilárd attempted to alert Washington, D.C. to ongoing Nazi atomic bomb research.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He was asked to lend his support by writing a letter, with Szilárd, to President Franklin D.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Roosevelt, recommending the US pay attention and engage in its own nuclear weapons research.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The letter is believed to be "arguably the key stimulus for the U.S. adoption of serious investigations into nuclear weapons on the eve of the U.S. entry into World War II".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In addition to the letter, Einstein used his connections with the Belgian royal family and the Belgian queen mother to get access with a personal envoy to the White House's Oval Office.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Some say that as a result of Einstein's letter and his meetings with Roosevelt, the US entered the "race" to develop the bomb, drawing on its "immense material, financial, and scientific resources" to initiate the Manhattan Project.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] For Einstein, "war was a disease ... [and] he called for resistance to war." By signing the letter to Roosevelt, some argue he went against his pacifist principles.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein became an American citizen in 1940.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Not long after settling into his career at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, he expressed his appreciation of the meritocracy in American culture compared to Europe.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He recognized the "right of individuals to say and think what they pleased" without social barriers.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] As a result, individuals were encouraged, he said, to be more creative, a trait he valued from his early education.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein joined the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Princeton, where he campaigned for the civil rights of African Americans.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He considered racism America's "worst disease", seeing it as "handed down from one generation to the next".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] As part of his involvement, he corresponded with civil rights activist W.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Du Bois and was prepared to testify on his behalf during his trial as an alleged foreign agent in 1951.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] When Einstein offered to be a character witness for Du Bois, the judge decided to drop the case.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In 1946, Einstein visited Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, a historically black college, where he was awarded an honorary degree.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Lincoln was the first university in the United States to grant college degrees to African Americans; alumni include Langston Hughes and Thurgood Marshall.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein gave a speech about racism in America, adding, "I do not intend to be quiet about it." A resident of Princeton recalls that Einstein had once paid the college tuition for a black student.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein has said, "Being a Jew myself, perhaps I can understand and empathize with how black people feel as victims of discrimination".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Isaacson writes that "When Marian Anderson, the black contralto, came to Princeton for a concert in 1937, the Nassau Inn refused her a room.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] So Einstein invited her to stay at his house on Main Street, in what was a deeply personal as well as symbolic gesture ...
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In 1918, Einstein was one of the signatories of the founding proclamation of the German Democratic Party, a liberal party.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Later in his life, Einstein's political view was in favor of socialism and critical of capitalism, which he detailed in his essays such as "Why Socialism?".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] His opinions on the Bolsheviks also changed with time.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In 1925, he criticized them for not having a "well-regulated system of government" and called their rule a "regime of terror and a tragedy in human history".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein offered and was called on to give judgments and opinions on matters often unrelated to theoretical physics or mathematics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He strongly advocated the idea of a democratic global government that would check the power of nation-states in the framework of a world federation.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote "I advocate world government because I am convinced that there is no other possible way of eliminating the most terrible danger in which man has ever found himself." The FBI created a secret dossier on Einstein in 1932; by the time of his death, it was 1,427 pages long.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was deeply impressed by Mahatma Gandhi, with whom he corresponded.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He described Gandhi as "a role model for the generations to come".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The initial connection was established on 27 September 1931, when Wilfrid Israel took his Indian guest V.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram to his friend Einstein's summer home in the town of Caputh to meet him.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram was Gandhi's disciple and special envoy, whom Wilfrid Israel met while visiting India and visiting the Indian leader's home in 1925.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] During the visit, Einstein wrote a short letter to Gandhi that was delivered to him through Sundaram, and Gandhi responded quickly with his own letter.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Although in the end Einstein and Gandhi were unable to meet as they had hoped, the direct connection between them was established through Wilfrid Israel.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein, a Jew, was a figurehead leader in the establishment of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, which opened in 1925.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Earlier, in 1921, he was asked by the biochemist and president of the World Zionist Organization, Chaim Weizmann, to help raise funds for the planned university.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He made suggestions for the creation of an Institute of Agriculture, a Chemical Institute and an Institute of Microbiology in order to fight the various ongoing epidemics such as malaria, which he called an "evil" that was undermining a third of the country's development.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He also promoted the establishment of an Oriental Studies Institute, to include language courses given in both Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was not a nationalist and opposed the creation of an independent Jewish state.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He felt that the waves of arriving Jews of the Aliyah could live alongside existing Arabs in Palestine.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The state of Israel was established without his help in 1948; Einstein was limited to a marginal role in the Zionist movement.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Afterward, Einstein adopted a practical attitude, understanding that "there is no going back", and the new state must be supported.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Upon the death of Israeli president Weizmann in November 1952, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion offered Einstein the largely ceremonial position of President of Israel at the urging of Ezriel Carlebach.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The offer was presented by Israel's ambassador in Washington, Abba Eban, who explained that the offer "embodies the deepest respect which the Jewish people can repose in any of its sons".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein wrote that he was "deeply moved", but "at once saddened and ashamed" that he could not accept it.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein did not want the office, and the Israeli government did not want him to accept, but felt obliged to make the offer.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Yitzhak Navon, Ben-Gurion's political secretary, and later president, reports Ben-Gurion as saying "Tell me what to do if he says yes!
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] I've had to offer the post to him because it's impossible not to.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Per Lee Smolin, "I believe what allowed Einstein to achieve so much was primarily a moral quality.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He simply cared far more than most of his colleagues that the laws of physics have to explain everything in nature coherently and consistently." Einstein expounded his spiritual outlook in a wide array of writings and interviews.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He said he had sympathy for the impersonal pantheistic God of Baruch Spinoza's philosophy.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He did not believe in a personal god who concerns himself with fates and actions of human beings, a view which he described as naïve.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He clarified, however, that "I am not an atheist", preferring to call himself an agnostic, or a "deeply religious nonbeliever".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote that "A spirit is manifest in the laws of the universe—a spirit vastly superior to that of man, and one in the face of which we with our modest powers must feel humble.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was primarily affiliated with non-religious humanist and Ethical Culture groups in both the UK and US.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He served on the advisory board of the First Humanist Society of New York, and was an honorary associate of the Rationalist Association, which publishes *New Humanist* in Britain.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] For the 75th anniversary of the New York Society for Ethical Culture, he stated that the idea of Ethical Culture embodied his personal conception of what is most valuable and enduring in religious idealism.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein had been sympathetic toward vegetarianism for a long time.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He became a vegetarian himself only during the last part of his life.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In March 1954 he wrote in a letter: "So I am living without fats, without meat, without fish, but am feeling quite well this way.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein developed an appreciation for music at an early age.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] His mother played the piano reasonably well and wanted her son to learn the violin, not only to instill in him a love of music but also to help him assimilate into German culture.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] According to conductor Leon Botstein, Einstein began playing when he was 5.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] However, he did not enjoy it at that age.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] When he turned 13, he discovered Mozart's violin sonatas, whereupon he became enamored of Mozart's compositions and studied music more willingly.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein taught himself to play without "ever practicing systematically".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He said that "love is a better teacher than a sense of duty".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] At the age of 17, he was heard by a school examiner in Aarau while playing Beethoven's violin sonatas.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] The examiner stated afterward that his playing was "remarkable and revealing of 'great insight'".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] What struck the examiner, writes Botstein, was that Einstein "displayed a deep love of the music, a quality that was and remains in short supply.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Music took on a pivotal and permanent role in Einstein's life from that period on.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Although the idea of becoming a professional musician himself was not on his mind at any time, among those with whom Einstein played chamber music were a few professionals, including Kurt Appelbaum, and he performed for private audiences and friends.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Chamber music had also become a regular part of his social life while living in Bern, Zurich, and Berlin, where he played with Max Planck and his son, among others.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He is sometimes erroneously credited as the editor of the 1937 edition of the Köchel catalog of Mozart's work; that edition was prepared by Alfred Einstein, who may have been a distant relation.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In 1931, while engaged in research at the California Institute of Technology, he visited the Zoellner family conservatory in Los Angeles, where he played some of Beethoven and Mozart's works with members of the Zoellner Quartet.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Near the end of his life, when the young Juilliard Quartet visited him in Princeton, he played his violin with them, and the quartet was "impressed by Einstein's level of coordination and intonation".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] On 17 April 1955, Einstein experienced internal bleeding caused by the rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm, which had previously been reinforced surgically by Rudolph Nissen in 1948.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] He took the draft of a speech he was preparing for a television appearance commemorating the state of Israel's seventh anniversary with him to the hospital, but he did not live to complete it.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein refused surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] I will do it elegantly." He died in the Princeton Hospital early the next morning at the age of 76, having continued to work until near the end.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] During the autopsy, the pathologist Thomas Stoltz Harvey removed Einstein's brain for preservation without the permission of his family, in the hope that the neuroscience of the future would be able to discover what made Einstein so intelligent.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's remains were cremated in Trenton, New Jersey, and his ashes were scattered at an undisclosed location.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] In a memorial lecture delivered on 13 December 1965 at UNESCO headquarters, nuclear physicist J.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Robert Oppenheimer summarized his impression of Einstein as a person: "He was almost wholly without sophistication and wholly without worldliness ...
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein bequeathed his personal archives, library, and intellectual assets to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Throughout his life, Einstein published hundreds of books and articles.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He published more than 300 scientific papers and 150 non-scientific ones.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] On 5 December 2014, universities and archives announced the release of Einstein's papers, comprising more than 30,000 unique documents.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to the work he did by himself, he also collaborated with other scientists on additional projects, including the Bose–Einstein statistics, the Einstein refrigerator and others.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's first paper, submitted in 1900 to *Annalen der Physik*, was on capillary attraction.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It was published in 1901 with the title "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen", which translates as "Conclusions from the capillarity phenomena".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Two papers he published in 1902–1903 (thermodynamics) attempted to interpret atomic phenomena from a statistical point of view.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] These papers were the foundation for the 1905 paper on Brownian motion, which showed that Brownian movement can be construed as firm evidence that molecules exist.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] His research in 1903 and 1904 was mainly concerned with the effect of finite atomic size on diffusion phenomena.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein returned to the problem of thermodynamic fluctuations, giving a treatment of the density variations in a fluid at its critical point.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Ordinarily, the density fluctuations are controlled by the second derivative of the free energy with respect to the density.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] At the critical point, this derivative is zero, leading to large fluctuations.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The effect of density fluctuations is that light of all wavelengths is scattered, making the fluid look milky white.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein relates this to Rayleigh scattering, which is what happens when the fluctuation size is much smaller than the wavelength, and which explains why the sky is blue.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein quantitatively derived critical opalescence from a treatment of density fluctuations, and demonstrated how both the effect and Rayleigh scattering originate from the atomistic constitution of matter.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The *Annus Mirabilis* papers are four articles pertaining to the photoelectric effect (which gave rise to quantum theory), Brownian motion, the special theory of relativity, and *E* = *mc*2 that Einstein published in the *Annalen der Physik* scientific journal in 1905.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] These four works contributed substantially to the foundation of modern physics and changed views on space, time, and matter.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's "*Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper*" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies") was received on 30 June 1905 and published 26 September of that same year.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It reconciled conflicts between Maxwell's equations (the laws of electricity and magnetism) and the laws of Newtonian mechanics by introducing changes to the laws of mechanics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Observationally, the effects of these changes are most apparent at high speeds (where objects are moving at speeds close to the speed of light).
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The theory developed in this paper later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This paper predicted that, when measured in the frame of a relatively moving observer, a clock carried by a moving body would appear to slow down, and the body itself would contract in its direction of motion.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This paper also argued that the idea of a luminiferous aether—one of the leading theoretical entities in physics at the time—was superfluous.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In his paper on mass–energy equivalence, Einstein produced *E* = *mc*2 as a consequence of his special relativity equations.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's 1905 work on relativity remained controversial for many years, but was accepted by leading physicists, starting with Max Planck.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein originally framed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies).
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski reinterpreted special relativity in geometric terms as a theory of spacetime.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein adopted Minkowski's formalism in his 1915 general theory of relativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity (GR) is a theory of gravitation that was developed by Einstein between 1907 and 1915.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] According to it, the observed gravitational attraction between masses results from the warping of spacetime by those masses.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity has developed into an essential tool in modern astrophysics; it provides the foundation for the current understanding of black holes, regions of space where gravitational attraction is so strong that not even light can escape.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] As Einstein later said, the reason for the development of general relativity was that the preference of inertial motions within special relativity was unsatisfactory, while a theory which from the outset prefers no state of motion (even accelerated ones) should appear more satisfactory.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, in 1907 he published an article on acceleration under special relativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In that article titled "On the Relativity Principle and the Conclusions Drawn from It", he argued that free fall is really inertial motion, and that for a free-falling observer the rules of special relativity must apply.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This argument is called the equivalence principle.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In the same article, Einstein also predicted the phenomena of gravitational time dilation, gravitational redshift and gravitational lensing.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1911, Einstein published another article "On the Influence of Gravitation on the Propagation of Light" expanding on the 1907 article, in which he estimated the amount of deflection of light by massive bodies.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Thus, the theoretical prediction of general relativity could for the first time be tested experimentally.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1916, Einstein predicted gravitational waves, ripples in the curvature of spacetime which propagate as waves, traveling outward from the source, transporting energy as gravitational radiation.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The existence of gravitational waves is possible under general relativity due to its Lorentz invariance which brings the concept of a finite speed of propagation of the physical interactions of gravity with it.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] By contrast, gravitational waves cannot exist in the Newtonian theory of gravitation, which postulates that the physical interactions of gravity propagate at infinite speed.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The first, indirect, detection of gravitational waves came in the 1970s through observation of a pair of closely orbiting neutron stars, PSR B1913+16.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The explanation for the decay in their orbital period was that they were emitting gravitational waves.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's prediction was confirmed on 11 February 2016, when researchers at LIGO published the first observation of gravitational waves, detected on Earth on 14 September 2015, nearly one hundred years after the prediction.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] While developing general relativity, Einstein became confused about the gauge invariance in the theory.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He formulated an argument that led him to conclude that a general relativistic field theory is impossible.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He gave up looking for fully generally covariant tensor equations and searched for equations that would be invariant under general linear transformations only.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In June 1913, the Entwurf ('draft') theory was the result of these investigations.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] As its name suggests, it was a sketch of a theory, less elegant and more difficult than general relativity, with the equations of motion supplemented by additional gauge fixing conditions.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] After more than two years of intensive work, Einstein realized that the hole argument was mistaken and abandoned the theory in November 1915.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, Einstein applied the general theory of relativity to the structure of the universe as a whole.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He discovered that the general field equations predicted a universe that was dynamic, either contracting or expanding.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] As observational evidence for a dynamic universe was lacking at the time, Einstein introduced a new term, the cosmological constant, into the field equations, in order to allow the theory to predict a static universe.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The modified field equations predicted a static universe of closed curvature, in accordance with Einstein's understanding of Mach's principle in these years.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This model became known as the Einstein World or Einstein's static universe.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This paper is widely regarded as marking the emergence of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Following the discovery of the recession of the galaxies by Edwin Hubble in 1929, Einstein abandoned his static model of the universe, and proposed two dynamic models of the cosmos, the Friedmann–Einstein universe of 1931 and the Einstein–de Sitter universe of 1932.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In each of these models, Einstein discarded the cosmological constant, claiming that it was "in any case theoretically unsatisfactory".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In many Einstein biographies, it is claimed that Einstein referred to the cosmological constant in later years as his "biggest blunder", based on a letter George Gamow claimed to have received from him.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The astrophysicist Mario Livio has cast doubt on this claim.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In late 2013, a team led by the Irish physicist Cormac O'Raifeartaigh discovered evidence that, shortly after learning of Hubble's observations of the recession of the galaxies, Einstein considered a steady-state model of the universe.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In a hitherto overlooked manuscript, apparently written in early 1931, Einstein explored a model of the expanding universe in which the density of matter remains constant due to a continuous creation of matter, a process that he associated with the cosmological constant.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It thus appears that Einstein considered a steady-state model of the expanding universe many years before Hoyle, Bondi and Gold.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] However, Einstein's steady-state model contained a fundamental flaw and he quickly abandoned the idea.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity includes a dynamical spacetime, so it is difficult to see how to identify the conserved energy and momentum.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Noether's theorem allows these quantities to be determined from a Lagrangian with translation invariance, but general covariance makes translation invariance into something of a gauge symmetry.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The energy and momentum derived within general relativity by Noether's prescriptions do not make a real tensor for this reason.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein argued that this is true for a fundamental reason: the gravitational field could be made to vanish by a choice of coordinates.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He maintained that the non-covariant energy momentum pseudotensor was, in fact, the best description of the energy momentum distribution in a gravitational field.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] While the use of non-covariant objects like pseudotensors was criticized by Erwin Schrödinger and others, Einstein's approach has been echoed by physicists including Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1935, Einstein collaborated with Nathan Rosen to produce a model of a wormhole, often called Einstein–Rosen bridges.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] His motivation was to model elementary particles with charge as a solution of gravitational field equations, in line with the program outlined in the paper "Do Gravitational Fields play an Important Role in the Constitution of the Elementary Particles?".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] These solutions cut and pasted Schwarzschild black holes to make a bridge between two patches.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Because these solutions included spacetime curvature without the presence of a physical body, Einstein and Rosen suggested that they could provide the beginnings of a theory that avoided the notion of point particles.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] However, it was later found that Einstein–Rosen bridges are not stable.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In order to incorporate spinning point particles into general relativity, the affine connection needed to be generalized to include an antisymmetric part, called the torsion.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This modification was made by Einstein and Cartan in the 1920s.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In general relativity, gravitational force is reimagined as curvature of spacetime.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] A curved path like an orbit is not the result of a force deflecting a body from an ideal straight-line path, but rather the body's attempt to fall freely through a background that is itself curved by the presence of other masses.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The geodesic equation covers the former aspect, stating that freely falling bodies follow lines that are as straight as possible in a curved spacetime.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein regarded this as an "independent fundamental assumption" that had to be postulated in addition to the field equations in order to complete the theory.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Believing this to be a shortcoming in how general relativity was originally presented, he wished to derive it from the field equations themselves.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Since the equations of general relativity are non-linear, a lump of energy made out of pure gravitational fields, like a black hole, would move on a trajectory which is determined by the Einstein field equations themselves, not by a new law.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Accordingly, Einstein proposed that the field equations would determine the path of a singular solution, like a black hole, to be a geodesic.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from applying the field equations to the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In a 1905 paper, Einstein postulated that light itself consists of localized particles (*quanta*).
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's light quanta were nearly universally rejected by all physicists, including Max Planck and Niels Bohr.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This idea only became universally accepted in 1919, with Robert Millikan's detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect, and with the measurement of Compton scattering.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein concluded that each wave of frequency *f* is associated with a collection of photons with energy *hf* each, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He did not say much more, because he was not sure how the particles were related to the wave.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] But he did suggest that this idea would explain certain experimental results, notably the photoelectric effect.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Light quanta were dubbed *photons* by Gilbert N.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1907, Einstein proposed a model of matter where each atom in a lattice structure is an independent harmonic oscillator.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In the Einstein model, each atom oscillates independently—a series of equally spaced quantized states for each oscillator.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein was aware that getting the frequency of the actual oscillations would be difficult, but he nevertheless proposed this theory because it was a particularly clear demonstration that quantum mechanics could solve the specific heat problem in classical mechanics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1924, Einstein received a description of a statistical model from Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, based on a counting method that assumed that light could be understood as a gas of indistinguishable particles.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein noted that Bose's statistics applied to some atoms as well as to the proposed light particles, and submitted his translation of Bose's paper to the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also published his own articles describing the model and its implications, among them the Bose–Einstein condensate phenomenon that some particulates should appear at very low temperatures.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It was not until 1995 that the first such condensate was produced experimentally by Eric Allin Cornell and Carl Wieman using ultra-cooling equipment built at the NIST–JILA laboratory at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Bose–Einstein statistics are now used to describe the behaviors of any assembly of bosons.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's sketches for this project may be seen in the Einstein Archive in the library of the Leiden University.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Although the patent office promoted Einstein to Technical Examiner Second Class in 1906, he had not given up on academia.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, he became a *Privatdozent* at the University of Bern.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This paper introduced the *photon* concept and inspired the notion of wave–particle duality in quantum mechanics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein saw this wave–particle duality in radiation as concrete evidence for his conviction that physics needed a new, unified foundation.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In a series of works completed from 1911 to 1913, Planck reformulated his 1900 quantum theory and introduced the idea of zero-point energy in his "second quantum theory".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Soon, this idea attracted the attention of Einstein and his assistant Otto Stern.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Assuming the energy of rotating diatomic molecules contains zero-point energy, they then compared the theoretical specific heat of hydrogen gas with the experimental data.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] However, after publishing the findings, they promptly withdrew their support, because they no longer had confidence in the correctness of the idea of zero-point energy.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, at the height of his work on relativity, Einstein published an article in *Physikalische Zeitschrift* that proposed the possibility of stimulated emission, the physical process that makes possible the maser and the laser.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This article showed that the statistics of absorption and emission of light would only be consistent with Planck's distribution law if the emission of light into a mode with n photons would be enhanced statistically compared to the emission of light into an empty mode.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This paper was enormously influential in the later development of quantum mechanics, because it was the first paper to show that the statistics of atomic transitions had simple laws.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein discovered Louis de Broglie's work and supported his ideas, which were received skeptically at first.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In another major paper from this era, Einstein observed that de Broglie waves could explain the quantization rules of Bohr and Sommerfeld.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This paper would inspire Schrödinger's work of 1926.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein played a major role in developing quantum theory, beginning with his 1905 paper on the photoelectric effect.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] However, he became displeased with modern quantum mechanics as it had evolved after 1925, despite its acceptance by other physicists.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He was skeptical that the randomness of quantum mechanics was fundamental rather than the result of determinism, stating that God "is not playing at dice".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Until the end of his life, he continued to maintain that quantum mechanics was incomplete.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The Bohr–Einstein debates were a series of public disputes about quantum mechanics between Einstein and Niels Bohr, who were two of its founders.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates are remembered because of their importance to the philosophy of science.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates would influence later interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein never fully accepted quantum mechanics.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] While he recognized that it made correct predictions, he believed a more fundamental description of nature must be possible.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Over the years he presented multiple arguments to this effect, but the one he preferred most dated to a debate with Bohr in 1930.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein suggested a thought experiment in which two objects are allowed to interact and then moved apart a great distance from each other.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The quantum-mechanical description of the two objects is a mathematical entity known as a wavefunction.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] If the wavefunction that describes the two objects before their interaction is given, then the Schrödinger equation provides the wavefunction that describes them after their interaction.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] But because of what would later be called quantum entanglement, measuring one object would lead to an instantaneous change of the wavefunction describing the other object, no matter how far away it is.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Moreover, the choice of which measurement to perform upon the first object would affect what wavefunction could result for the second object.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein reasoned that no influence could propagate from the first object to the second instantaneously fast.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Indeed, he argued, physics depends on being able to tell one thing apart from another, and such instantaneous influences would call that into question.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Because the true "physical condition" of the second object could not be immediately altered by an action done to the first, Einstein concluded, the wavefunction could not be that true physical condition, only an incomplete description of it.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] A more famous version of this argument came in 1935, when Einstein published a paper with Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen that laid out what would become known as the EPR paradox.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In this thought experiment, two particles interact in such a way that the wavefunction describing them is entangled.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Then, no matter how far the two particles were separated, a precise position measurement on one particle would imply the ability to predict, perfectly, the result of measuring the position of the other particle.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Likewise, a precise momentum measurement of one particle would result in an equally precise prediction for of the momentum of the other particle, without needing to disturb the other particle in any way.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] They argued that no action taken on the first particle could instantaneously affect the other, since this would involve information being transmitted faster than light, which is forbidden by the theory of relativity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] But quantum mechanics considers these two observables incompatible and thus does not associate simultaneous values for both to any system.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen therefore concluded that quantum theory does not provide a complete description of reality.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1964, John Stewart Bell carried the analysis of quantum entanglement much further.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He deduced that if measurements are performed independently on the two separated particles of an entangled pair, then the assumption that the outcomes depend upon hidden variables within each half implies a mathematical constraint on how the outcomes on the two measurements are correlated.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This constraint would later be called a Bell inequality.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Bell then showed that quantum physics predicts correlations that violate this inequality.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, the only way that hidden variables could explain the predictions of quantum physics is if they are "nonlocal", which is to say that somehow the two particles are able to interact instantaneously no matter how widely they ever become separated.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Bell argued that because an explanation of quantum phenomena in terms of hidden variables would require nonlocality, the EPR paradox "is resolved in the way which Einstein would have liked least".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Despite this, and although Einstein personally found the argument in the EPR paper overly complicated, that paper became among the most influential papers published in *Physical Review*.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It is considered a centerpiece of the development of quantum information theory.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Encouraged by his success with general relativity, Einstein sought an even more ambitious geometrical theory that would treat gravitation and electromagnetism as aspects of a single entity.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1950, he described his unified field theory in a *Scientific American* article titled "On the Generalized Theory of Gravitation".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] His attempt to find the most fundamental laws of nature won him praise but not success: a particularly conspicuous blemish of his model was that it did not accommodate the strong and weak nuclear forces, neither of which was well understood until many years after his death.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Although most researchers now believe that Einstein's approach to unifying physics was mistaken, his goal of a theory of everything is one to which his successors still aspire.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein conducted other investigations that were unsuccessful and abandoned.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] These pertain to force, superconductivity, and other research.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to longtime collaborators Leopold Infeld, Nathan Rosen, Peter Bergmann and others, Einstein also had some one-shot collaborations with various scientists.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Owen Willans Richardson predicted that a change in the magnetic moment of a free body will cause this body to rotate.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This effect is a consequence of the conservation of angular momentum and is strong enough to be observable in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein and Wander Johannes de Haas published two papers in 1915 claiming the first experimental observation of the effect.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Measurements of this kind demonstrate that the phenomenon of magnetization is caused by the alignment (polarization) of the angular momenta of the electrons in the material along the axis of magnetization.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] These measurements also allow the separation of the two contributions to the magnetization: that which is associated with the spin and with the orbital motion of the electrons.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The Einstein-de Haas experiment is the only experiment conceived, realized and published by Albert Einstein himself.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] A complete original version of the Einstein-de Haas experimental equipment was donated by Geertruida de Haas-Lorentz, wife of de Haas and daughter of Lorentz, to the Ampère Museum in Lyon France in 1961 where it is currently on display.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It was lost among the museum's holdings and was rediscovered in 2023.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1926, Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd co-invented (and in 1930, patented) the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] This absorption refrigerator was then revolutionary for having no moving parts and using only heat as an input.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] On 11 November 1930, U.S. patent 1,781,541 was awarded to Einstein and Leó Szilárd for the refrigerator.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Their invention was not immediately put into commercial production, but the most promising of their patents were acquired by the Swedish company Electrolux.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also invented an electromagnetic pump, sound reproduction device, and several other household devices.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] While traveling, Einstein wrote daily to his wife Elsa and adopted stepdaughters Margot and Ilse.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The letters were included in the papers bequeathed to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Margot Einstein permitted the personal letters to be made available to the public, but requested that it not be done until twenty years after her death (she died in 1986).
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Barbara Wolff, of the Hebrew University's Albert Einstein Archives, told the BBC that there are about 3,500 pages of private correspondence written between 1912 and 1955.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In his final four years, Einstein was involved with the establishment of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York City.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1979, the Albert Einstein Memorial was unveiled outside the National Academy of Sciences building in Washington, D.C. for the Einstein centenary.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein can be seen holding a paper with three of his most important equations: for the photoelectric effect, general relativity and mass-energy equivalence.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's right of publicity was litigated in 2015 in a federal district court in California.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Although the court initially held that the right had expired, that ruling was immediately appealed, and the decision was later vacated in its entirety.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The underlying claims between the parties in that lawsuit were ultimately settled.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The right is enforceable, and the Hebrew University of Jerusalem is the exclusive representative of that right.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Corbis, successor to The Roger Richman Agency, licenses the use of his name and associated imagery, as agent for the university.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in the Chugach Mountains of Alaska was named in 1955.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, Einstein was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, a survey of the top 100 physicists voted for Einstein as the "greatest physicist ever", while a parallel survey of rank-and-file physicists gave the top spot to Isaac Newton, with Einstein second.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Simmons ranked Einstein second after Newton in *The Scientific 100*, based on a qualitative assessment in which he ordered the scientists according to overall influence, and noted that the work of Einstein "forms the source of twentieth-century physics".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics declared 2005 the "World Year of Physics", also known as "Einstein Year", in recognition of Einstein's "miracle year" in 1905.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] It was also declared the "International Year of Physics" by the United Nations.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein became one of the most famous scientific celebrities after the confirmation of his general theory of relativity in 1919.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Although most of the public had little understanding of his work, he was widely recognized and admired.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] In the period before World War II, *The New Yorker* published a vignette in their "The Talk of the Town" feature saying that Einstein was so well known in America that he would be stopped on the street by people wanting him to explain "that theory".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Eventually he came to cope with unwanted enquirers by pretending to be someone else: "Pardon me, sorry!
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein has been the subject of or inspiration for many novels, films, plays, and works of music.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] He is a favorite model for depictions of absent-minded professors; his expressive face and distinctive hairstyle have been widely copied and exaggerated.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] *Time* magazine's Frederic Golden wrote that Einstein was "a cartoonist's dream come true".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] His intellectual achievements and originality made *Einstein* broadly synonymous with *genius*.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Many popular quotations are often misattributed to him.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein received numerous awards and honors, and in 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] The Nobel committee decided that none of the nominations in 1921 met the criteria set by Alfred Nobel, so the 1921 prize was carried forward and awarded to Einstein in 1922.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] Einsteinium, a synthetic chemical element, was named in his honor in 1955, a few months after his death.
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] (Public Domain) *Einstein, Albert (1926).
[src:technocracy-movement/albert-einstein-p04] London & New York: The Encyclopædia Britannica Company. pp.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He was a key figure in the early history of the Russian Social Democratic Labor Party, originally established 1898, and of its Bolshevik faction.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1904–1906, he published three volumes of the philosophic treatise *Empiriomonizm* (*Empiriomonism*), in which he tried to merge Marxism with the philosophy of Ernst Mach, Wilhelm Ostwald, and Richard Avenarius.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] His work later affected a number of Russian Marxist theoreticians, including Nikolai Bukharin and Dov Ber Borochov.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov co-founded the Bolsheviks in 1903, when they split with the Menshevik faction.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He was a rival within the Bolsheviks to Vladimir Lenin (1870–1924), Lenin concentrated on undermining Bogdanov's reputation as a philosopher.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1909 he published a scathing book of criticism entitled *Materialism and Empiriocriticism*, assaulting Bogdanov's position and accusing him of philosophical idealism.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In June 1909, Bogdanov was defeated by Lenin at a Bolshevik mini-conference in Paris organized by the editorial board of the Bolshevik magazine *Proletary* and was expelled from the Bolsheviks.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He subsequently established his own faction Vpered.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Following the Russian Revolutions of 1917, when the Bolsheviks came to power in the collapsing Russian Republic, he was an influential critic of the Bolshevik government and Lenin from a Marxist leftist perspective during the first decade of the subsequent Soviet Union in the 1920s.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov received training in medicine and psychiatry.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] His wide scientific and medical interests ranged from the universal systems theory to the possibility of human rejuvenation through blood transfusion.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He invented an original philosophy called "tectology", now regarded as a forerunner of systems theory.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He was also an economist, culture theorist, science fiction writer, and political activist.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Lenin depicted him as one of the "Russian Machists".
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] A Russian born in Belarus, Alexander Malinovsky was born in Sokółka, Russian Empire (now Poland), into a rural teacher's family, the second of six children.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He attended the Gymnasium at Tula, which he compared to a barracks or prison.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He was awarded a gold medal when he graduated.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Upon completion of the gymnasium, Bogdanov was admitted to the Natural Science Department of Imperial Moscow University.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In his autobiography, Bogdanov reported that, while studying at Moscow University, he joined the Union Council of Regional Societies and was arrested and exiled to Tula because of it.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] The head of the Moscow Okhrana had used an informant to acquire the names of members of the Union Council of Regional Societies, which included Bogdanov's name.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] On October 30, 1894, students rowdily demonstrated against a lecture by the history Professor Vasily Klyuchevsky who, despite being a well-known liberal, had written a favourable eulogy for the recently deceased Tsar Alexander III of Russia.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Punishment of a few of the students was seen as so arbitrary and unfair that the Union Council requested a fair reexamination of the issue.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] That very night, the Okhrana arrested all the students on the list mentioned above – including Bogdanov – all of whom were expelled from the university and banished to their hometowns.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Expelled from Moscow State University, he enrolled as an external student at the University of Kharkov, from which he graduated as a physician in 1899.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov remained in Tula from 1894 to 1899, where – since his own family was living in Sokółka – he lodged with Alexander Rudnev, the father of Vladimir Bazarov, who became a close friend and collaborator in future years.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Here he met and married Natalya Bogdanovna Korsak, who, as a woman, had been refused entrance to the university.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] She was eight years older than he was and worked as a nurse for Rudnev.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Malinovsky adopted the pen name that he used when he wrote his major theoretical works and his novels from her patronym.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Alongside Bazarov and Ivan Skvortsov-Stepanov he became a tutor in a workers' study circle.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] This was organised in the Tula Armament Factory by Ivan Saveliev, whom Bogdanov credited with founding Social Democracy in Tula.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] During this period, he wrote his *Brief course of economic science*, which was published – "subject to many modifications made for the benefit of the censor" – only in 1897.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He later said that this experience of student-led education gave him his first lesson in proletarian culture.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In autumn 1895, he resumed his medical studies at the university of Kharkiv (Ukraine) but still spent much time in Tula.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He came across the works of Lenin in 1896, particularly the latter's critique of Peter Berngardovich Struve.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1899, he graduated as a medical doctor and published his next work, "Basic elements of the historical perspective on nature".
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] However, because of his political views, he was also arrested by the Tsar's police, spent six months in prison, and was exiled to Vologda.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov dated his support for Bolshevism from autumn of 1903.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Early in 1904, the Bolsheviks in Geneva sent Martyn Liadov to seek out supporters in Russia.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He found a sympathetic group of revolutionaries, including Bogdanov, in Tver.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov was then sent by the Tver Committee to Geneva, where he was greatly impressed by Lenin's *One Step Forward, Two Steps Back* (published in May 1904).
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Back in Russia at the time of the 1905 Revolution, Bogdanov was arrested on 3 December 1905 and held in prison until 27 May 1906.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Upon release, he was exiled for three years to Bezhetsk in the Tver Governorate.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] However, he obtained permission to spend his exile abroad, and joined Lenin in Kokkola, Finland.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] For the next six years, Bogdanov was a major figure among the early Bolsheviks, second only to Lenin in influence.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] His work later affected a number of Russian Marxist theoreticians, including Nikolai Bukharin.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1907, he helped organize the 1907 Tiflis bank robbery with both Lenin and Leonid Krasin.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1908 he joined Bazarov, Lunacharsky, Berman, Helfond, Yushkevich and Suvorov in a symposium *Studies in the Philosophy of Marxism* which espoused the views of the Russian Marxists.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] By mid-1908, the factionalism within the Bolsheviks had become irreconcilable.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] A majority of Bolshevik leaders either supported Bogdanov or were undecided between him and Lenin.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Lenin concentrated on undermining Bogdanov's reputation as a philosopher.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He joined his brother-in-law Anatoly Lunacharsky, Maxim Gorky, and other Vperedists on the island of Capri, where they started the Capri Party School for Russian factory-workers.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1910, Bogdanov, Lunacharsky, Mikhail Pokrovsky, and their supporters moved the school to Bologna, where they continued teaching classes until 1911, while Lenin and his allies soon started the Longjumeau Party School just outside of Paris.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov broke with the *Vpered* in 1912 and abandoned revolutionary activities.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] After six years of his political exile in Europe, Bogdanov returned to Russia in 1914, following the political amnesty declared by Tsar Nicholas II as part of the festivities connected with the tercentenary of the Romanov Dynasty.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov was drafted soon after the outbreak of World War I and was assigned as a junior regimental doctor with the 221st Smolensk infantry division in the Second Army commanded by General Alexander Samsonov.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In the Battle of Tannenberg, August 26–30, the Second Army was surrounded and almost completely destroyed, but Bogdanov survived because he had been sent to accompany a seriously wounded officer to Moscow.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] However following the Second Battle of the Masurian Lakes, he succumbed to a nervous disorder and subsequently became junior house surgeon at an evacuation hospital.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] In 1916 he wrote four articles for *Vpered* which provided an analysis of the World War I and the dynamics of war economies.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He attributed a central role to the armed forces in the economic restructuring of the belligerent powers.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He saw the army as creating a "consumers' communism" with the state taking over ever-increasing parts of the economy.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] At the same time military authoritarianism had also spread to civil society.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] This created the conditions for two consequences: consumption-led war communism and the destruction of the means of production.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] He thus predicted that even after the war, the new system of state capitalism would replace that of finance capitalism even though the destruction of the forces of production would cease.
[src:technocracy-movement/alexander-bogdanov] Bogdanov had no party-political involvement in the Russian Revolution of 1917, although he did publish a number of articles and books about the events that unfurled around him.
